# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: androsthenes-of-thasos
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Born in Pella, Macedon, Alexander was tutored by philosopher and polymath Aristotle until the age of 16.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] In 335 BC, shortly after assuming the throne of Macedon, he launched a campaign in the Balkans and reasserted control over Thrace and parts of Illyria before marching on the city of Thebes, which was subsequently destroyed.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander then assumed leadership of the League of Corinth, created by his father.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] With this authority over all Greeks he launched a pan-Hellenic invasion of the Persian Achaemenid Empire in 334 BC, and with it began a series of campaigns which lasted for ten years.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Following his conquest of Asia Minor and a series of decisive battles, particularly at Issus and Gaugamela, the power of the Achaemenid Empire was broken.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] He subsequently overthrew Darius III and conquered the Achaemenid Empire in its entirety.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] After the fall of Persia, the Macedonian Empire held a vast swath of territory between the Adriatic Sea and the Indus River.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander endeavored to reach the "ends of the world and the Great Outer Sea" and invaded India in 326 BC, achieving an important victory over Porus, an ancient Indian king of present-day Punjab, at the Battle of the Hydaspes.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Facing mutiny from troops, he was eventually forced to turn back at the Beas River, and later died in 323 BC in Babylon, Mesopotamia, the city which he had planned to make the capital of his empire, while on his return to Greece.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander's death put an end to his planned invasion of Arabia.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] In the years following his death, a series of civil wars broke out across the Macedonian Empire, eventually leading to its disintegration at the hands of the Diadochi.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander's death marks the conventional beginning of the Hellenistic period.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Through his conquests, he built a legacy that includes the cultural diffusion and syncretism, which gave rise to Greco-Buddhism and Hellenistic Judaism.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] He founded more than twenty cities, with the most prominent being the city of Alexandria in Egypt.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander's establishment of Greek colonies and the spreading of Greek culture led to Hellenistic civilization becoming a major force in the ancient world, influencing regions as far east as the Indian subcontinent.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] The Hellenistic period developed through the Roman Empire into modern Western culture; the Greek language became the *lingua franca* of the region and was the predominant language of the Byzantine Empire until its collapse in 1453 AD.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander became a legendary hero similar to Achilles, featuring prominently in the historical and mythical traditions of both Greek and non-Greek cultures.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] His military achievements and successes in battle made him the touchstone against which many later military leaders would judge themselves.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] His tactics remain a significant subject of study in military academies worldwide.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Legends of Alexander's exploits were coalesced into the 3rd century *Alexander Romance* which, in the premodern period, went through over one hundred recensions, translations, and derivations and was translated into almost every European vernacular and every language of the Islamic world.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] After the Bible, it was the most popular form of European literature.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander III was born in Pella, the capital of the Kingdom of Macedon, on the sixth day of the ancient Greek month of Hekatombaion, which probably corresponds to 20 July 356 BC (although the exact date is uncertain).
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] He was the son of the king of Macedon, Philip II of the Argead dynasty and his fourth wife, Olympias (daughter of Neoptolemus I, Aeacid king of Epirus).
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Although Philip had seven or eight wives, Olympias was his principal wife for some time, likely because she gave birth to Alexander.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Several legends surround Alexander's birth and childhood.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] According to the ancient Greek biographer Plutarch, on the eve of the consummation of her marriage to Philip, Olympias dreamed that her womb was struck by a thunderbolt that caused a flame to spread "far and wide" before dying away.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Sometime after the wedding, Philip is said to have seen himself, in a dream, securing his wife's womb with a seal engraved with a lion's image.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Plutarch offered a variety of interpretations for these dreams: that Olympias was pregnant before her marriage, indicated by the sealing of her womb; or that Alexander's father was Zeus.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Ancient commentators were divided about whether the ambitious Olympias promulgated the story of Alexander's divine parentage, variously claiming that she had told Alexander, or that she dismissed the suggestion as impious.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] On the day Alexander was born, Philip was preparing a siege on the city of Potidea on the peninsula of Chalcidice.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] That same day, Philip received news that his general Parmenion had defeated the combined Illyrian and Paeonian armies and that his horses had won at the Olympic Games.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] It was also said that on this day, the Temple of Artemis in Ephesus, one of the Seven Wonders of the World, burnt down.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] This led Hegesias of Magnesia to say that it had burnt down because Artemis was away, attending the birth of Alexander.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Such legends may have emerged when Alexander was king, and possibly at his instigation, to show that he was superhuman and destined for greatness from conception.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] In his early years, Alexander was raised by a nurse, Lanike, sister of Alexander's future general Cleitus the Black.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Later in his childhood, Alexander was tutored by the strict Leonidas, a relative of his mother, and by Lysimachus of Acarnania.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander was raised in the manner of noble Macedonian youths, learning to read, play the lyre, ride, fight, and hunt.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] When Alexander was ten years old, a trader from Thessaly brought Philip a horse, which he offered to sell for thirteen talents.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] The horse refused to be mounted, and Philip ordered it away.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander, however, detecting the horse's fear of its own shadow, asked to tame the horse, which he eventually managed.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Plutarch stated that Philip, overjoyed at this display of courage and ambition, kissed his son tearfully, declaring: "My boy, you must find a kingdom big enough for your ambitions.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Macedon is too small for you", and bought the horse for him.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander named it Bucephalas, meaning "ox-head".
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Bucephalas carried Alexander as far as modern day India.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] When Bucephalas died (because of old age, according to Plutarch, at age 30), Alexander named a city after him, Bucephala.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] When Alexander was 13, Philip began to search for a tutor, and considered such academics as Isocrates and Speusippus, the latter offering to resign from his stewardship of the Academy to take up the post.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] In the end, Philip chose Aristotle and provided the Temple of the Nymphs at Mieza as a classroom.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] In return for teaching Alexander, Philip agreed to rebuild Aristotle's hometown of Stageira, which Philip had razed, and to repopulate it by buying and freeing the ex-citizens who were slaves, or pardoning those who were in exile.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Mieza was like a boarding school for Alexander and the children of Macedonian nobles, such as Ptolemy, Hephaestion, and Cassander.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Many of these students would become his friends and future generals, and are often known as the "Companions".
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Aristotle taught Alexander and his companions about medicine, philosophy, morals, religion, logic, and art.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Under Aristotle's tutelage, Alexander developed a passion for the works of Homer, and in particular the *Iliad*; Aristotle gave him an annotated copy, which Alexander later carried on his campaigns.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander was able to quote Euripides from memory.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] In his youth, Alexander was also acquainted with Persian exiles at the Macedonian court, who received the protection of Philip II for several years as they opposed Artaxerxes III.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Among them were Artabazos II and his daughter Barsine, possible future mistress of Alexander, who resided at the Macedonian court from 352 to 342 BC, as well as Amminapes, future satrap of Alexander, and a Persian nobleman named Sisines.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] This gave the Macedonian court a good knowledge of Persian issues, and may even have influenced some of the innovations in the management of the Macedonian state.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Suda writes that Anaximenes of Lampsacus was one of Alexander's teachers, and that Anaximenes also accompanied Alexander on his campaigns.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] At the age of 16, Alexander's education under Aristotle ended.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Philip II had waged war against the Thracians to the north, which left Alexander in charge as regent and heir apparent.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] During Philip's absence, the Thracian tribe of Maedi revolted against Macedonia.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander responded quickly and drove them from their territory.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] The territory was colonized, and a city, named Alexandropolis, was founded.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Upon Philip's return, Alexander was dispatched with a small force to subdue the revolts in southern Thrace.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Campaigning against the Greek city of Perinthus, Alexander reportedly saved his father's life.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Meanwhile, the city of Amphissa began to work lands that were sacred to Apollo near Delphi, a sacrilege that gave Philip the opportunity to further intervene in Greek affairs.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] While Philip was occupied in Thrace, Alexander was ordered to muster an army for a campaign in southern Greece.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Concerned that other Greek states might intervene, Alexander made it look as though he was preparing to attack Illyria instead.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] During this turmoil, the Illyrians invaded Macedonia, only to be repelled by Alexander.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Philip and his army joined his son in 338 BC, and they marched south through Thermopylae, taking it after stubborn resistance from its Theban garrison.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] They went on to occupy the city of Elatea, only a few days' march from both Athens and Thebes.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] The Athenians, led by Demosthenes, voted to seek alliance with Thebes against Macedonia.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Both Athens and Philip sent embassies to win Thebes's favour, but Athens won the contest.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Philip marched on Amphissa (ostensibly acting on the request of the Amphictyonic League), capturing the mercenaries sent there by Demosthenes and accepting the city's surrender.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Philip then returned to Elatea, sending a final offer of peace to Athens and Thebes, who both rejected it.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] As Philip marched south, his opponents blocked him near Chaeronea, Boeotia.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] During the ensuing Battle of Chaeronea, Philip commanded the right wing and Alexander the left, accompanied by a group of Philip's trusted generals.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] According to the ancient sources, the two sides fought bitterly for some time.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Philip deliberately commanded his troops to retreat, counting on the untested Athenian hoplites to follow, thus breaking their line.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander was the first to break the Theban lines, followed by Philip's generals.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Having damaged the enemy's cohesion, Philip ordered his troops to press forward and quickly routed them.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] With the Athenians lost, the Thebans were surrounded.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Left to fight alone, they were defeated.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Following their victory at Chaeronea, Philip and Alexander marched unopposed into the Peloponnese, devastating much of Laconia and ejecting the Spartans from various parts of it.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] At Corinth, Philip established a "Hellenic Alliance" (modelled on the old anti-Persian alliance of the Greco-Persian Wars), which included most Greek city-states except Sparta.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Philip was then named *Hegemon* (often translated as "Supreme Commander") of this league (known by modern scholars as the League of Corinth), and announced his plans to attack the Persian Empire.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] When Philip returned to Pella, he fell in love with and married Cleopatra Eurydice in 338 BC, the niece of his general Attalus.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] The marriage made Alexander's position as heir less secure, since any son of Cleopatra Eurydice would be a fully Macedonian heir, while Alexander was only half-Macedonian.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] During the wedding banquet, a drunken Attalus publicly prayed to the gods that the union would produce a legitimate heir.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] — Plutarch, describing the feud at Philip's wedding.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] In 337 BC, Alexander fled Macedon with his mother, dropping her off with her brother, King Alexander I of Epirus in Dodona, capital of the Molossians.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] He continued to Illyria where he sought refuge with one or more Illyrian kings, perhaps with Glaucias, and was treated as a guest, despite having defeated them in battle a few years before.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] However, it appears Philip never intended to disown his politically and militarily trained son.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Accordingly, Alexander returned to Macedon after six months due to the efforts of a family friend, Demaratus, who mediated between the two parties.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] In the following year, the Persian satrap (governor) of Caria, Pixodarus, offered his eldest daughter to Alexander's half-brother, Philip Arrhidaeus.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Olympias and several of Alexander's friends suggested this showed Philip intended to make Arrhidaeus his heir.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander reacted by sending an actor, Thessalus of Corinth, to tell Pixodarus that he should not offer his daughter's hand to an illegitimate son, but instead to Alexander.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] When Philip heard of this, he stopped the negotiations and scolded Alexander for wishing to marry the daughter of a Carian, explaining that he wanted a better bride for him.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Philip exiled four of Alexander's friends, Harpalus, Nearchus, Ptolemy and Erigyius, and had the Corinthians bring Thessalus to him in chains.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] As Pausanias tried to escape, he tripped over a vine and was killed by his pursuers, including two of Alexander's companions, Perdiccas and Leonnatus.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander was proclaimed king on the spot by the nobles and army at the age of 20.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander began his reign by eliminating potential rivals to the throne.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] He had his cousin, the former Amyntas IV, executed and two Macedonian princes from the region of Lyncestis killed for having been involved in his father's assassination, but spared a third, Alexander Lyncestes.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Olympias had Cleopatra Eurydice, and Europa, her daughter by Philip, burned alive, though this infuriated Alexander.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander also ordered the murder of Cleopatra's uncle Attalus, who was in command of the advance guard of the army in Asia Minor.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Attalus was at that time corresponding with Demosthenes regarding the possibility of defecting to Athens, and had severely insulted Alexander.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] After his niece's murder, Alexander may have considered him too dangerous to be left alive.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander spared Arrhidaeus, who was by all accounts mentally disabled, possibly as a result of poisoning by Olympias.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] News of Philip's death roused many states into revolt, including Thebes, Athens, Thessaly, and the Thracian tribes north of Macedon.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] When news of the revolts reached Alexander, he responded quickly.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Though advised to use diplomacy, Alexander mustered 3,000 Macedonian cavalry and rode south towards Thessaly.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] He found the Thessalian army occupying the pass between Mount Olympus and Mount Ossa, and ordered his men to ride over Mount Ossa.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] When the Thessalians awoke the next day, they found Alexander in their rear and promptly surrendered, adding their cavalry to Alexander's force.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] He then continued south towards the Peloponnese.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander stopped at Thermopylae where he was recognized as the leader of the Amphictyonic League before heading south to Corinth.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Athens sued for peace and Alexander pardoned the rebels.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] The famous encounter between Alexander and Diogenes the Cynic occurred during Alexander's stay in Corinth.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] When Alexander asked Diogenes what he could do for him, the philosopher disdainfully asked Alexander to stand a little to the side, as he was blocking the sunlight.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] This reply apparently delighted Alexander who is reported to have said, "But verily, if I were not Alexander, I would like to be Diogenes." At Corinth, Alexander took the title of *Hegemon* ("leader") and, like Philip, was appointed commander for the coming war against Persia.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] He also received news of a Thracian uprising.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Before crossing to Asia, Alexander wanted to safeguard his northern borders.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] In the spring of 335 BC, he advanced to suppress several revolts.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Starting from Amphipolis, he travelled east into the country of the "Independent Thracians", and at Mount Haemus, the Macedonian army attacked and defeated the Thracian forces manning the heights.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] The Macedonians marched into the country of the Triballi and defeated their army near the Lyginus river (a tributary of the Danube).
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander then marched for three days to the Danube, encountering the Getae tribe on the opposite shore.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Crossing the river at night, he surprised them and forced their army to retreat after the first cavalry skirmish.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] News then reached Alexander that the Illyrian chieftain Cleitus and King Glaukias of the Taulantii were in open revolt against his authority.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Marching west into Illyria, Alexander defeated each in turn, forcing the two rulers to flee with their troops.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] With these victories, he secured his northern frontier.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] While Alexander campaigned north, the Thebans and Athenians rebelled once again.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] While the other cities again hesitated, Thebes decided to fight.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] The Theban resistance was ineffective and Alexander razed the city and divided its territory between the other Boeotian cities.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] The end of Thebes cowed Athens, leaving all of Greece temporarily at peace.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander then set out on his Asian campaign, leaving Antipater as regent.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] After securing his Greek base and the Balkans by subjugating his political opponents, and securing his army's rear through the conquest of all the Afro-Asian coastline, where the Persian fleet was based and from which it was supplied, Alexander moved to confront directly the Persians.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] In 336 he sent Parmenion, Amyntas, Andromenes, Attalus, and an army of 10,000 men into Anatolia to make preparations for an invasion.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] The Greek cities on the western coast of Anatolia revolted until the news arrived that Philip had been murdered and had been succeeded by his young son Alexander.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] The Macedonians were demoralized by Philip's death and were subsequently defeated near Magnesia by the Achaemenids under the command of the mercenary Memnon of Rhodes.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] He showed his intent to conquer the entirety of the Persian Empire by throwing a spear into Asian soil and saying he accepted Asia as a gift from the gods.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] This also showed Alexander's eagerness to fight, in contrast to his father's preference for diplomacy.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] After an initial victory against Persian forces at the Battle of the Granicus, Alexander accepted the surrender of the Persian provincial capital and treasury of Sardis; he then proceeded along the Ionian coast, granting autonomy and democracy to the cities.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Miletus, held by Achaemenid forces, required a delicate siege operation, with Persian naval forces nearby.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Further south, at Halicarnassus, in Caria, Alexander successfully waged his first large-scale siege, eventually forcing his opponents, the mercenary captain Memnon of Rhodes and the Persian satrap of Caria, Orontobates, to withdraw by sea.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander left the government of Caria to a member of the Hecatomnid dynasty, Ada, who adopted Alexander.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] From Halicarnassus, Alexander proceeded into mountainous Lycia and the Pamphylian plain, asserting control over all coastal cities to deny the Persians naval bases.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] From Pamphylia onwards, the coast held no major ports and Alexander moved inland.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] At Termessos, Alexander humbled and did not storm the Pisidian city.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] At the ancient Phrygian capital of Gordium, Alexander "undid" the hitherto unsolvable Gordian Knot, a feat said to await the future "king of Asia".
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] According to the story, Alexander proclaimed that it did not matter how the knot was undone, and hacked it apart with his sword.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] In spring 333 BC, Alexander crossed the Taurus into Cilicia.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] After a long pause due to an illness, he marched on towards Syria.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Though outmanoeuvered by Darius's significantly larger army, he marched back to Cilicia, where he defeated Darius at Issus.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Darius fled the battle, causing his army to collapse, and left behind his wife, his two daughters, his mother Sisygambis, and a fabulous treasure.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] He offered a peace treaty that included the lands he had lost, and a ransom of 10,000 talents for his family.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander replied that since he was now king of Asia, it was he alone who decided territorial divisions.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander proceeded to take possession of Syria, and most of the coast of the Levant.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] In the following year, 332 BC, he was forced to attack Tyre, which he captured after a long and difficult siege.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] The men of military age were massacred and the women and children sold into slavery.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] When Alexander destroyed Tyre, most of the towns on the route to Egypt quickly capitulated.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] However, Alexander was met with resistance at Gaza.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] The stronghold was heavily fortified and built on a hill, requiring a siege.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] When "his engineers pointed out to him that because of the height of the mound it would be impossible... this encouraged Alexander all the more to make the attempt".
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] After three unsuccessful assaults, the stronghold fell, but not before Alexander had received a serious shoulder wound.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] As in Tyre, men of military age were put to the sword, and the women and children were sold into slavery.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander advanced on Egypt in later 332 BC where he was regarded as a liberator.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] To legitimize taking power and be recognized as the descendant of the long line of pharaohs, Alexander made sacrifices to the gods at Memphis and went to consult the famous oracle of Amun-Ra at the Siwa Oasis in the Libyan desert, at which he was pronounced the son of the deity Amun.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Henceforth, Alexander often referred to Zeus-Ammon as his true father, and after his death, currency depicted him adorned with horns, using the Horns of Ammon as a symbol of his divinity.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] The Greeks interpreted this message – one that the gods addressed to all pharaohs – as a prophecy.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Egypt was only one of a large number of territories taken by Alexander from the Persians.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] After his trip to Siwa, Alexander was crowned in the temple of Ptah at Memphis.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] It appears that the Egyptian people did not find it disturbing that he was a foreigner – nor that he was absent for virtually his entire reign.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander restored the temples neglected by the Persians and dedicated new monuments to the Egyptian gods.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] In the temple of Luxor, near Karnak, he built a chapel for the sacred barge.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] During his brief months in Egypt, he reformed the taxation system on the Greek models and organized the military occupation of the country, but in early 331 BC he left for Asia in pursuit of the Persians.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] During his stay in Egypt, he founded Alexandria, which would become the prosperous capital of the Ptolemaic Kingdom after his death.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Control of Egypt passed to Ptolemy I (son of Lagos), the founder of the Ptolemaic Dynasty (305–30 BC) after the death of Alexander.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Leaving Egypt in 331 BC, Alexander marched eastward into Achaemenid Assyria in Upper Mesopotamia (now northern Iraq) and defeated Darius again at the Battle of Gaugamela.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Darius once more fled the field, and Alexander chased him as far as Arbela.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Gaugamela would be the final and decisive encounter between the two.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Darius fled over the mountains to Ecbatana (modern Hamadan) while Alexander captured Babylon.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Babylonian astronomical diaries say that "the king of the world, Alexander" sent his scouts with a message to the people of Babylon before entering the city: "I shall not enter your houses".
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] From Babylon, Alexander went to Susa, one of the Achaemenid capitals, and captured its treasury.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] He sent the bulk of his army to the Persian ceremonial capital of Persepolis via the Persian Royal Road.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander himself took selected troops on the direct route to the city.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] He then stormed the pass of the Persian Gates (in the modern Zagros Mountains) which had been blocked by a Persian army under Ariobarzanes and then hurried to Persepolis before its garrison could loot the treasury.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] On entering Persepolis, Alexander allowed his troops to loot the city for several days.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander stayed in Persepolis for five months.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] During his stay, a fire broke out in the eastern palace of Xerxes I and spread to the rest of the city.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Possible causes include a drunken accident or deliberate revenge for the burning of the Acropolis of Athens during the Second Persian War by Xerxes; Plutarch and Diodorus allege that Alexander's companion, the hetaera Thaïs, instigated and started the fire.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Even as he watched the city burn, Alexander immediately began to regret his decision.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Plutarch claims that he ordered his men to put out the fires but the flames had already spread to most of the city.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Curtius claims that Alexander did not regret his decision until the next morning.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander then chased Darius, first into Media, and then Parthia.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] The Persian king no longer controlled his own destiny, and was taken prisoner by Bessus, his Bactrian satrap and kinsman.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] As Alexander approached, Bessus had his men fatally stab the Great King and then declared himself Darius's successor as Artaxerxes V, before retreating into Central Asia to launch a guerrilla campaign against Alexander.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander buried Darius's remains next to his Achaemenid predecessors in a regal funeral.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] He claimed that, while dying, Darius had named him as his successor to the Achaemenid throne.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] The Achaemenid Empire is normally considered to have fallen with Darius.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander viewed Bessus as an usurper and set out to defeat him.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] This campaign, initially against Bessus, turned into a grand tour of central Asia.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander founded a series of new cities, all called Alexandria, including modern Kandahar in Afghanistan, and Alexandria Eschate ("The Furthest") in modern Tajikistan.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] The campaign took Alexander through a number of satrapies in present-day Afghanistan and Central Asia, including Media, Parthia, Aria, Drangiana, Arachosia, Bactria, and Scythia.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] In 329 BC, Spitamenes, who held an undefined position in the satrapy of Sogdiana, betrayed Bessus to Ptolemy, one of Alexander's trusted companions, and Bessus was executed.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] However, at some point later when Alexander was on the Jaxartes dealing with an incursion by a horse nomad army, Spitamenes raised Sogdiana in revolt.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander personally defeated the Scythians at the Battle of Jaxartes and immediately launched a campaign against Spitamenes, defeating him in the Battle of Gabai.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] After the defeat, Spitamenes was killed by his own men, who then sued for peace.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] During this time, Alexander adopted some elements of Persian dress and customs at his court, notably the custom of *proskynesis*, either a symbolic kissing of the hand, or prostration on the ground, that Persians showed to their social superiors.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] This was one aspect of Alexander's broad strategy aimed at securing the aid and support of the Iranian upper classes.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] The Greeks however regarded the gesture of *proskynesis* as the province of deities and believed that Alexander meant to deify himself by requiring it.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] This cost him the sympathies of many of his countrymen, and he eventually abandoned it.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] During the long rule of the Achaemenids, the elite positions in many segments of the empire including the central government, the army, and the many satrapies were specifically reserved for Iranians and to a major degree, Persian noblemen.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] The latter were in many cases additionally connected through marriage alliances with the royal Achaemenid family.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] This created a problem for Alexander as to whether he had to make use of the various segments and people that had given the empire its solidity and unity for a lengthy period of time.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Pierre Briant explains that Alexander realized that it was insufficient to merely exploit the internal contradictions within the imperial system as in Asia Minor, Babylonia or Egypt; he also had to (re)create a central government with or without the support of the Iranians.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] As early as 334 BC he demonstrated awareness of this, when he challenged incumbent King Darius III "by appropriating the main elements of the Achaemenid monarchy's ideology, particularly the theme of the king who protects the lands and the peasants".
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander wrote a letter in 332 BC to Darius III, wherein he argued that he was worthier than Darius "to succeed to the Achaemenid throne".
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] However, Alexander's eventual decision to burn the Achaemenid palace at Persepolis in conjunction with the major rejection and opposition of the "entire Persian people" made it impracticable for him to pose himself as Darius' legitimate successor.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Against Bessus (Artaxerxes V) however, Briant adds, Alexander reasserted "his claim to legitimacy as the avenger of Darius III".
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] A plot against his life was revealed, and one of his officers, Philotas, was executed for failing to alert Alexander.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] The death of the son necessitated the death of the father, and thus Parmenion, who had been charged with guarding the treasury at Ecbatana, was assassinated at Alexander's command, to prevent attempts at vengeance.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Later, in the Central Asian campaign, a second plot against his life was revealed.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] This one was instigated by his own royal pages.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] His official historian, Callisthenes of Olynthus, was implicated in the plot, and in the *Anabasis of Alexander*, Arrian states that Callisthenes and the pages were then tortured on the rack as punishment, and likely died soon after.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] It remains unclear if Callisthenes was actually involved in the plot, for prior to his accusation he had fallen out of favour by leading the opposition to the attempt to introduce proskynesis.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] When Alexander set out for Asia, he left his general Antipater, an experienced military and political leader, and part of Philip II's "Old Guard", in charge of Macedon.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander's sacking of Thebes ensured that Greece remained quiet during his absence.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] The one exception was a call to arms by Spartan king Agis III in 331 BC, whom Antipater defeated and killed in the battle of Megalopolis.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Antipater referred the Spartans' punishment to the League of Corinth, which then deferred to Alexander, who chose to pardon them.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] There was also considerable friction between Antipater and Olympias, and each complained to Alexander about the other.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] In general, Greece enjoyed a period of peace and prosperity during Alexander's campaign in Asia.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander sent back vast sums from his conquest, which stimulated the economy and increased trade across his empire.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] However, Alexander's constant demands for troops and the migration of Macedonians throughout his empire depleted Macedon's strength, greatly weakening it in the years after Alexander, and ultimately led to its subjugation by Rome after the Third Macedonian War (171–168 BC).
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] The conquest by Philip II of Pangaeum, and then of the island of Thasos between 356 and 342 BC brought rich gold and silver mines under Macedonian control.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander appears to have introduced a new coinage in Cilicia in Tarsus, after the Battle of Issus in 333 BC, which went on to become the main coinage of the empire.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander minted gold staters, silver tetradrachms and drachims, and various fractional bronze coins.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] The types of these coins remained constant in his empire.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] The gold series had the head of Athena on the obverse and a winged Nike (Victory) on the reverse.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] The silver coinage had a beardless head of Heracles wearing a lionskin headdress on the obverse and Zeus aetophoros ('eagle bearer') enthroned with a scepter in his left hand, on the reverse.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] There are both Greek and non-Greek aspects to this design.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Heracles and Zeus were important deities for the Macedonians, with Heracles considered to be the ancestor of the Temenid dynasty and Zeus the patron of the main Macedonian sanctuary, Dium.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] The lion was also the symbolic animal of the Anatolian god Sandas, worshipped at Tarsus.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] The reverse design of Alexander's tetradrachms is closely modelled on the depiction of the god Baaltars (Baal of Tarsus), on the silver staters minted at Tarsus by the Persian satrap Mazaeus before Alexander's conquest.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander did not attempt to impose uniform imperial coinage throughout his new conquests.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Persian coins continued to circulate in all the satrapies of the empire.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] After the death of Spitamenes and his marriage to Roxana (Raoxshna in Old Iranian) to cement relations with his new satrapies, Alexander turned to the Indian subcontinent.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] He invited the chieftains of the former satrapy of Gandhara (in the present-day Peshawar Valley), to come to him and submit to his authority.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] In the winter of 327/326 BC, Alexander personally led Cophen campaign against the Aspasioi of the Kunar Valley, the Guraeans of the Panjkora Valley, and the Assakenoi of the Swat Valley.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] A fierce contest ensued with the Aspasioi in which Alexander was wounded in the shoulder by a dart, but eventually the Aspasioi lost.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander then faced the Assakenoi who fought against him from the strongholds of Massaga, Ora, and Aornos.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] The fort of Massaga was reduced after days of bloody fighting in which Alexander was seriously wounded in the ankle.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] According to Curtius, "Not only did Alexander slaughter the entire population of Massaga, but also did he reduce its buildings to rubble." A similar massacre followed at Ora.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] In the aftermath of Massaga and Ora, numerous Assakenians fled to the fortress of Aornos.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander followed close behind and captured the strategic hill-fort after four bloody days.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] After the death of Assakenoi leader, his mother queen Cleophis submitted to Alexander.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] After Aornos, Alexander crossed the Indus.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Omphis hastened to relieve Alexander of his apprehension and met him with valuable presents, placing himself and all his forces at his disposal.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander not only returned Omphis his title and the gifts but he also presented him with a wardrobe of "Persian robes, gold and silver ornaments, 30 horses and 1,000 talents in gold".
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] On the subsequent advance of the Macedonian king, Omphis accompanied him with a force of 5,000 men and took part in the Battle of the Hydaspes against the King Porus, who ruled territory lying between the Hydaspes and the Acesines (Chenab) in the Punjab, in 326 BC.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander won an epic battle against Porus.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Omphis was sent by Alexander in pursuit of Porus, to whom he was charged to offer favourable terms, but narrowly escaped losing his life at the hands of his old enemy.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Subsequently, the two rivals were reconciled by the personal mediation of Alexander; Omphis contributed zealously to the equipment of the fleet on the Hydaspes and was entrusted by Alexander with the government of the whole territory between that river and the Indus.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander was also impressed by Porus's bravery and made him an ally.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] He appointed Porus as satrap, and added to Porus's territory land that he did not previously own, towards the south-east, up to the Hyphasis (Beas).
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Choosing local rulers helped him control these lands that were distant from Greece.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] A considerable accession of power was granted him after the death of Philip, son of Machatas, and he was allowed to retain his authority at the death of Alexander himself (323 BC), as well as in the subsequent partition of the provinces at Triparadisus, 321 BC.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander founded two cities on opposite sides of the Hydaspes river, naming one Bucephala, in honour of his horse, who died around this time.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] The other was Nicaea (Victory), believed to be located at the site of modern-day Mong.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Philostratus the Elder in the *Life of Apollonius of Tyana* writes that in the army of Porus, there was an elephant who fought bravely against Alexander's army, and Alexander dedicated it to the Helios (Sun) and named it Ajax because he thought that such a great animal deserved a great name.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] The elephant had gold rings around its tusks and an inscription was on them written in Greek: "Alexander the son of Zeus dedicates Ajax to the Helios" (ΑΛΕΞΑΝΔΡΟΣ Ο ΔΙΟΣ ΤΟΝ ΑΙΑΝΤΑ ΤΩΙ ΗΛΙΩΙ).
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] East of Porus's kingdom, near the Ganges River, was the Nanda Empire of Magadha, and further east, the Gangaridai Empire of Bengal region.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Fearing the prospect of facing other large armies and exhausted by years of campaigning, Alexander's army mutinied at the Hyphasis River (Beas), refusing to march farther east.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] This river thus marks the easternmost extent of Alexander's conquests.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander tried to persuade his soldiers to march farther, but his general Coenus pleaded with him to change his opinion and return; the men, he said, "longed to again see their parents, their wives and children, their homeland".
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander eventually agreed and turned south, marching along the Indus.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Along the way his army conquered the territory inhabited by the Mallians in the Mallian campaign; while besieging the Mallian citadel, Alexander suffered a near-fatal injury when an arrow penetrated his armor and entered his lung.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander sent much of his army to Carmania (modern southern Iran) with general Craterus, and commissioned a fleet to explore the Persian Gulf shore under his admiral Nearchus, while he led the rest back to Persia through the more difficult southern route along the Gedrosian Desert and Makran.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander reached Susa in 324 BC, but not before losing many men to the harsh desert.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Discovering that many of his satraps and military governors had misbehaved in his absence, Alexander executed several of them as examples on his way to Susa.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] As a gesture of thanks, he paid off the debts of his soldiers, and announced he would send over-aged and disabled veterans back to Macedon, led by Craterus.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] His troops misunderstood his intention and mutinied at the town of Opis.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] They refused to be sent away and criticized his adoption of Persian customs and dress and the introduction of Persian officers and soldiers into Macedonian units.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] After three days, unable to persuade his men to back down, Alexander gave Persians command posts in the army and conferred Macedonian military titles upon Persian units.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] The Macedonians quickly begged forgiveness, which Alexander accepted, and held a great banquet with several thousand of his men.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] In an attempt to craft a lasting harmony between his Macedonian and Persian subjects, Alexander held a mass marriage of his senior officers to Persian and other noblewomen at Susa, but few of those marriages seem to have lasted much beyond a year.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Meanwhile, upon his return to Persia, Alexander learned that guards of the tomb of Cyrus the Great in Pasargadae had desecrated it, and swiftly executed them.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Alexander admired Cyrus the Great, from an early age reading Xenophon's *Cyropaedia*, which described Cyrus's heroism in battle and governance as a king and legislator.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] During his visit to Pasargadae, Alexander ordered his architect Aristobulus to decorate the interior of the sepulchral chamber of Cyrus's tomb.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Afterwards, Alexander travelled to Ecbatana to retrieve the bulk of the Persian treasure.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] There, his closest friend, Hephaestion, died of illness or poisoning.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Hephaestion's death devastated Alexander and he ordered the preparation of an expensive funeral pyre in Babylon along with a decree for public mourning.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p01] Back in Babylon, Alexander planned a series of new campaigns, beginning with an invasion of Arabia.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] On either 10 or 11 June 323 BC, Alexander died in the palace of Nebuchadnezzar II, in Babylon, at age 32.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] There are two different versions of Alexander's death, differing slightly in details.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] Plutarch's account is that roughly 14 days before his death, Alexander entertained admiral Nearchus and spent the night and next day drinking with Medius of Larissa.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] Alexander developed a fever, which worsened until he was unable to speak.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] The common soldiers, anxious about his health, were granted the right to file past him as he silently waved at them.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] In the second account, Diodorus recounts that Alexander was struck with pain after downing a large bowl of unmixed wine in honour of Heracles followed by 11 days of weakness; he did not develop a fever, instead dying after some agony.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] Arrian also mentioned this as an alternative, but Plutarch specifically denied this claim.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] Given the propensity of the Macedonian aristocracy to assassination and Alexander's relatively young age, foul play featured in multiple accounts of his death.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] Diodorus, Plutarch, Arrian and Justin all mentioned the theory that Alexander was poisoned.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] Justin stated that Alexander was the victim of a poisoning conspiracy, Plutarch dismissed it as a fabrication, while both Diodorus and Arrian noted that they mentioned it only for the sake of completeness.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] The accounts were nevertheless fairly consistent in designating Antipater, recently removed as Macedonian viceroy, replaced by Craterus, as the head of the alleged plot.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] Perhaps taking his summons to Babylon as a death sentence and having seen the fate of Parmenion and Philotas, Antipater purportedly arranged for Alexander to be poisoned by his son Iollas, who was Alexander's wine-pourer.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] There was even a suggestion that Aristotle may have participated.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] The strongest argument against the poison theory is the fact that twelve days passed between the start of his illness and his death; such long-acting poisons were probably not available.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] However, in a 2003 BBC documentary investigating the death of Alexander, Leo Schep from the New Zealand National Poisons Centre proposed that the plant white hellebore (*Veratrum album*), which was known in antiquity, may have been used to poison Alexander.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] In a 2014 manuscript in the journal *Clinical Toxicology*, Schep suggested Alexander's wine was spiked with *Veratrum album*, and that this would produce poisoning symptoms that match the course of events described in the *Alexander Romance*.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] *Veratrum album* poisoning can have a prolonged course and it was suggested that if Alexander was poisoned, *Veratrum album* offers the most plausible cause.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] Another poisoning explanation put forward in 2010 proposed that the circumstances of his death were compatible with poisoning by water of the river Styx (modern-day Mavroneri in Arcadia, Greece) that contained calicheamicin, a dangerous compound produced by bacteria.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] Several natural causes (diseases) have been suggested, including malaria and typhoid fever.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] A 1998 article in the *New England Journal of Medicine* attributed his death to typhoid fever complicated by bowel perforation and ascending paralysis.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] A 2004 analysis suggested pyogenic (infectious) spondylitis or meningitis.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] Other illnesses fit the symptoms, including acute pancreatitis, West Nile virus, and Guillain-Barré syndrome.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] Natural-cause theories also tend to emphasize that Alexander's health may have been in general decline after years of heavy drinking and severe wounds.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] The anguish that Alexander felt after Hephaestion's death may also have contributed to his declining health.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] Alexander's body was laid in a gold anthropoid sarcophagus that was filled with honey, which was in turn placed in a gold casket.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] According to Aelian, a seer called Aristander foretold that the land where Alexander was laid to rest "would be happy and unvanquishable forever".
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] Perhaps more likely, the successors may have seen possession of the body as a symbol of legitimacy, since burying the prior king was a royal prerogative.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] While Alexander's funeral cortege was on its way to Macedon, Ptolemy seized it and took it temporarily to Memphis.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] His successor, Ptolemy II Philadelphus, transferred the sarcophagus to Alexandria, where it remained until at least late antiquity.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] Ptolemy IX Lathyros, one of Ptolemy's final successors, replaced Alexander's sarcophagus with a glass one so he could convert the original to coinage.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] The 2014 discovery of an enormous tomb in northern Greece, at Amphipolis, dating from the time of Alexander the Great has given rise to speculation that its original intent was to be the burial place of Alexander.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] This would fit with the intended destination of Alexander's funeral cortege.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] However, the memorial was found to be dedicated to the dearest friend of Alexander the Great, Hephaestion.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] Pompey, Julius Caesar and Augustus all visited the tomb in Alexandria where Augustus, allegedly, accidentally knocked the nose of Alexander's mummified body off.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] Caligula was said to have taken Alexander's breastplate from the tomb for his own use.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] Around AD 200, Emperor Septimius Severus closed Alexander's tomb to the public.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] His son and successor, Caracalla, a great admirer, visited the tomb during his own reign.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] After this, details on the fate of the tomb are hazy.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] The so-called "Alexander Sarcophagus", discovered near Sidon and now in the Istanbul Archaeology Museum, is so named not because it was thought to have contained Alexander's remains, but because its bas-reliefs depict Alexander and his companions fighting the Persians and hunting.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] It was originally thought to have been the sarcophagus of Abdalonymus (died 311 BC), the king of Sidon appointed by Alexander immediately following the Battle of Issus in 332.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] However, in 1969, it was suggested by Karl Schefold that it may date from earlier than Abdalonymus's death.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] Demades likened the Macedonian army, after the death of Alexander, to the blinded Cyclops due to the many random and disorderly movements that it made.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] In addition, Leosthenes also likened the anarchy between the generals, after Alexander's death, to the blinded Cyclops "who after he had lost his eye went feeling and groping about with his hands before him, not knowing where to lay them".
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] Alexander's death was so sudden that when reports of his death reached Greece, they were not immediately believed.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] Alexander had no obvious or legitimate heir, his son Alexander IV by Roxane being born after Alexander's death.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] According to Diodorus, Alexander's companions asked him on his deathbed to whom he bequeathed his kingdom; his laconic reply was "tôi kratistôi"—"to the strongest".
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] Another theory is that his successors wilfully or erroneously misheard "tôi Kraterôi"—"to Craterus", the general leading his Macedonian troops home and newly entrusted with the regency of Macedonia.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] Arrian and Plutarch claimed that Alexander was speechless by this time, implying that this was an apocryphal story.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] Diodorus, Curtius and Justin offered the more plausible story that Alexander passed his signet ring to Perdiccas, a bodyguard and leader of the companion cavalry, in front of witnesses, thereby nominating him.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] Perdiccas initially did not claim power, instead suggesting that Roxane's baby would be king, if male, with himself, Craterus, Leonnatus, and Antipater as guardians.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] However, the infantry, under the command of Meleager, rejected this arrangement since they had been excluded from the discussion.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] Instead, they supported Alexander's half-brother Philip Arrhidaeus.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] Eventually, the two sides reconciled, and after the birth of Alexander IV, he and Philip III were appointed joint kings, albeit in name only.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] Dissension and rivalry soon affected the Macedonians.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] The satrapies handed out by Perdiccas at the Partition of Babylon became power bases each general used to bid for power.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] After the assassination of Perdiccas in 321 BC, Macedonian unity collapsed, and 40 years of war between "The Successors" (*Diadochi*) ensued before the Hellenistic world settled into three stable power blocs: Ptolemaic Egypt, Seleucid Syria and Persia, and Antigonid Macedonia.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] In the process, both Alexander IV and Philip III were murdered.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] Diodorus stated that Alexander had given detailed written instructions to Craterus some time before his death, which are known as Alexander's "last plans".
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] Craterus started to carry out Alexander's commands, but the successors chose not to further implement them, on the grounds they were impractical and extravagant.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] Furthermore, Perdiccas had read the notebooks containing Alexander's last plans to the Macedonian troops in Babylon, who voted not to carry them out.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] According to Diodorus, Alexander's last plans called for military expansion into the southern and western Mediterranean, monumental constructions, and the intermixing of Eastern and Western populations.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] The enormous scale of these plans has led many scholars to doubt their historicity.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] Ernst Badian argued that they were exaggerated by Perdiccas in order to ensure that the Macedonian troops voted not to carry them out.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] Other scholars have proposed that they were invented by later authors within the tradition of the Alexander Romance.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] Alexander perhaps earned the epithet "the Great" due to his unparalleled success as a military commander; he never lost a battle, despite typically being outnumbered.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] This was due to use of terrain, phalanx and cavalry tactics, bold strategy, and the fierce loyalty of his troops.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] The Macedonian phalanx, armed with the sarissa, a spear 6 metres (20 ft) long, had been developed and perfected by Philip II through rigorous training, and Alexander used its speed and manoeuvrability to great effect against larger but more disparate Persian forces.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] Alexander also recognized the potential for disunity among his diverse army, which employed various languages and weapons.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] He overcame this by being personally involved in battle, in the manner of a Macedonian king.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] In his first battle in Asia, at Granicus, Alexander used only a small part of his forces, perhaps 13,000 infantry with 5,000 cavalry, against a much larger Persian force of 40,000.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] Alexander placed the phalanx at the center and cavalry and archers on the wings, so that his line matched the length of the Persian cavalry line, about 3 km (1.86 mi).
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] By contrast, the Persian infantry was stationed behind its cavalry.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] This ensured that Alexander would not be outflanked, while his phalanx, armed with long pikes, had a considerable advantage over the Persians' scimitars and javelins.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] Macedonian losses were negligible compared to those of the Persians.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] At Issus in 333 BC, his first confrontation with Darius, he used the same deployment, and again the central phalanx pushed through.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] Alexander personally led the charge in the center, routing the opposing army.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] At the decisive encounter with Darius at Gaugamela, Darius equipped his chariots with scythes on the wheels to break up the phalanx and equipped his cavalry with pikes.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] Alexander arranged a double phalanx, with the center advancing at an angle, parting when the chariots bore down and then reforming.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] The advance was successful and broke Darius's center, causing the latter to flee once again.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] When faced with opponents who used unfamiliar fighting techniques, such as in Central Asia and India, Alexander adapted his forces to his opponents' style.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] Thus, in Bactria and Sogdiana, Alexander successfully used his javelin throwers and archers to prevent outflanking movements, while massing his cavalry at the center.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] In India, confronted by Porus's elephant corps, the Macedonians opened their ranks to envelop the elephants and used their sarissas to strike upwards and dislodge the elephants' handlers.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] Historical sources frequently give conflicting accounts of Alexander's appearance, and the earliest sources are the most scant in their detail; for example, Arrian describes him simply as "very handsome".
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] During his lifetime, Alexander carefully curated his image by commissioning works from famous and great artists of the time.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] This included commissioning sculptures by Lysippos, paintings by Apelles and gem engravings by Pyrgoteles.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] Ancient authors recorded that Alexander was so pleased with portraits of himself created by Lysippos that he forbade other sculptors from crafting his image; scholars today, however, find the claim dubious.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] Nevertheless, though idealised, Lysippos's sculpture was thought to be the most faithful plastic representation.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] 3rd century BC bust of Alexander from Alexandria, Egypt.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] Both Curtius and Diodorus report a story that when Darius III's mother, Sisygambis, first met Alexander and Hephaestion, she assumed that the latter was Alexander because he was the taller and more physically impressive of the two.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] Historians have understood the detail of the pleasant fragrance attributed to Alexander as stemming from a belief in ancient Greece that pleasant scents are characteristic of gods and heroes.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] The Alexander Mosaic and contemporary coins portray Alexander with "a straight nose, a slightly protruding jaw, full lips and eyes deep set beneath a strongly pronounced forehead".
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] He is also described as having a slight upward tilt of his head to the left.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] 235 AD), in his *Varia Historia* (12.14), describes Alexander's hair color as "ξανθὴν" (*xanthen*), which at the time, could mean blond, brown, tawny (light brown) or auburn.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] It is sometimes claimed that Alexander had one blue and one brown eye, referring to the *Alexander Romance*, which is however a fictional account that also claims Alexander "had sharp teeth like fangs" and "did not look like Philip or Olympias".
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] Reconstruction, based on remaining traces of paint of the original polychromy on the Alexander Sarcophagus from Sidon, indicates that he was depicted with brown eyes and chestnut brown hair.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] The Acropolis Museum suggests that trace amounts of red paint on a head statue of Alexander found in 1886 were most likely a base coat for golden hues to be painted over for his hair.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] The Pella mosaic of a lion hunt (late 4th century BC) depicts him as having blond hair, with empty spots where their eye stones (which would've been used with semi-precious gems) having been plucked out.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] Both of Alexander's parents encouraged his ambitions.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] His father Philip was probably Alexander's most immediate and influential role model, as the young Alexander watched him campaign practically every year, winning victory after victory while ignoring severe wounds.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] Alexander's relationship with his father "forged" the competitive side of his personality; he had a need to outdo his father, illustrated by his reckless behavior in battle.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] While Alexander worried that his father would leave him "no great or brilliant achievement to be displayed to the world", he also downplayed his father's achievements to his companions.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] Alexander's mother Olympias similarly had huge ambitions, and encouraged her son to believe it was his destiny to conquer the Persian Empire.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] She instilled a sense of destiny in him, and Plutarch tells how his ambition "kept his spirit serious and lofty in advance of his years".
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] According to Plutarch, Alexander also had a violent temper and rash, impulsive nature, which could influence his decision making.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] Although Alexander was stubborn and did not respond well to orders from his father, he was open to reasoned debate.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] He had a calmer side—perceptive, logical, and calculating.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] He had a great desire for knowledge, a love for philosophy, and was an avid reader.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] This was no doubt in part due to Aristotle's tutelage; Alexander was intelligent and quick to learn.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] His intelligent and rational side was amply demonstrated by his ability and success as a general.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] He had great self-restraint in "pleasures of the body", in contrast with his lack of self-control with alcohol.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] Alexander was erudite and patronized both arts and sciences.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] However, he had little interest in sports or the Olympic Games (unlike his father), seeking only the Homeric ideals of honour (*timê*) and glory (*kudos*).
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] He had great charisma and force of personality, characteristics which made him a great leader.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] His unique abilities were further demonstrated by the inability of any of his generals to unite Macedonia and retain the Empire after his death—only Alexander had the ability to do so.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] During his final years, and especially after the death of Hephaestion, Alexander began to exhibit signs of megalomania and paranoia.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] His extraordinary achievements, coupled with his own ineffable sense of destiny and the flattery of his companions, may have combined to produce this effect.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] His delusions of grandeur are readily visible in his will and in his desire to conquer the world, in as much as he is by various sources described as having *boundless ambition*, an epithet, the meaning of which has descended into a historical cliché.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] He appears to have believed himself a deity, or at least sought to deify himself.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] Olympias always insisted to him that he was the son of Zeus, an idea apparently confirmed to him by the oracle of Amun at Siwa.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] He began to identify himself as the son of Zeus-Ammon.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] This behaviour cost him the sympathies of many of his countrymen.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] Alexander also was a pragmatic ruler who understood the difficulties of ruling culturally disparate peoples, many of whom lived in societies where the king was treated as divine.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] Thus, rather than megalomania, his behaviour may have been a practical attempt at strengthening his rule and keeping his empire together.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] Alexander married three times: Roxana, daughter of the Sogdian nobleman Oxyartes of Bactria, out of love; the Persian princesses Stateira and Parysatis, the former a daughter of Darius III and the latter a daughter of Artaxerxes III, for political reasons.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] Alexander apparently had two children by Roxana: a son, who was born in India and died in infancy in November 326 BC, and Alexander IV of Macedon, born after his father's death.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] Additionally Heracles of Macedon was claimed to be his illegitimate son born of mistress, Barsine.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] Alexander also had a close relationship with his friend, general, and bodyguard Hephaestion, the son of a Macedonian noble.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] Hephaestion's death devastated Alexander.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] This event may have contributed to Alexander's failing health and detached mental state during his final months.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] Alexander's sexuality has been the subject of speculation and controversy in modern times.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] The Roman era writer Athenaeus says, based on the scholar Dicaearchus, who was Alexander's contemporary, that the king "was quite excessively keen on boys", and that Alexander kissed the eunuch Bagoas in public.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] This episode is also told by Plutarch, probably based on the same source.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] Historian William Woodthorpe Tarn rejected the stories of Bagoas as fabricated in ancient times to defame Alexander, mainly referring to the Rufus's fairly fictionalized biography of Alexander that criticized the Macedonian's "degeneration" in embracing foreign Persian customs.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] However, in 1958 Badian countered Tarn's arguments, though his concern was the issue of the reliability of sources for Alexander rather than the figure of the eunuch himself.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] None of Alexander's contemporaries, however, are known to have explicitly described Alexander's relationship with Hephaestion as sexual, though the pair was often compared to Achilles and Patroclus, who are often interpreted as a couple.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] Some modern historians (e.g., Robin Lane Fox) believe not only that Alexander's youthful relationship with Hephaestion was sexual, but also that their sexual contacts may have continued into adulthood, which went against the social norms of at least some Greek cities, such as Athens.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] However, some modern researchers have tentatively proposed that Macedonia (or at least the Macedonian court) may have been more tolerant of homosexuality between adults.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] Peter Green argues that there is little evidence in ancient sources that Alexander had much sexual interest in women; he did not produce an heir until the very end of his life.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] However, Ogden calculates that Alexander, who impregnated his partners three times in eight years, had fathered more children than his father at the same age.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] Two of these pregnancies—Stateira's and Barsine's—are of dubious legitimacy.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] According to Diodorus Siculus, Alexander accumulated a harem in the style of Persian kings, but he used it rather sparingly, "not wishing to offend the Macedonians", showing great self-control in "pleasures of the body".
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] Nevertheless, Plutarch described how Alexander was infatuated by Roxana while complimenting him on not forcing himself on her.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] Green suggested that, in the context of the period, Alexander formed quite strong friendships with women, including Ada of Caria, who adopted him, and even Darius's mother Sisygambis, who supposedly died from grief upon hearing of Alexander's death.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] Alexander's legacy extended beyond his military conquests, and his reign marked a turning point in European and Asian history.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] His campaigns greatly increased contacts and trade between East and West, and vast areas to the east were significantly exposed to Greek civilization and influence.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] Some of the cities he founded became major cultural centers, many surviving into the 21st century.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] His chroniclers recorded valuable information about the areas through which he marched, while the Greeks themselves got a sense of belonging to a world beyond the Mediterranean.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] Alexander's most immediate legacy was the introduction of Macedonian rule to huge new swathes of Asia.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] At the time of his death, Alexander's empire covered some 5,200,000 km2 (2,000,000 sq mi), and was the largest state of its time.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] Many of these areas remained in Macedonian hands or under Greek influence for the next 200–300 years.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] The successor states that emerged were, at least initially, dominant forces, and these 300 years are often referred to as the Hellenistic period.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] The eastern borders of Alexander's empire began to collapse even during his lifetime.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] However, the power vacuum he left in the northwest of the Indian subcontinent directly gave rise to one of the most powerful Indian dynasties in history, the Maurya Empire.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] Taking advantage of this power vacuum, Chandragupta Maurya (referred to in Greek sources as "Sandrokottos"), of relatively humble origin, took control of the Punjab, and with that power base proceeded to conquer the Nanda Empire.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] Over the course of his conquests, Alexander founded many cities that bore his name, most of them east of the Tigris.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] The first, and greatest, was Alexandria in Egypt, which would become one of the leading Mediterranean cities.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] The cities' locations reflected trade routes as well as defensive positions.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] At first, the cities must have been inhospitable, little more than defensive garrisons.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] Following Alexander's death, many Greeks who had settled there tried to return to Greece.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] However, a century or so after Alexander's death, many of the Alexandrias were thriving, with elaborate public buildings and substantial populations that included both Greek and local peoples.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] In 334 BC, Alexander the Great donated funds for the completion of the new temple of Athena Polias in Priene, in modern-day western Turkey.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] An inscription from the temple, now housed in the British Museum, declares: "King Alexander dedicated [this temple] to Athena Polias." This inscription is one of the few independent archaeological discoveries confirming an episode from Alexander's life.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] The temple was designed by Pytheos, one of the architects of the Mausoleum at Halicarnassus.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] Libanius wrote that Alexander founded the temple of Zeus Bottiaios (Ancient Greek: Βοττιαίου Δῖός), in the place where later the city of Antioch was built.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] Suda wrote that Alexander built a big temple to Sarapis.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] In 2023, British Museum experts have suggested the possibility that a Greek temple at Girsu in Iraq, was founded by Alexander.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] According to the researchers, recent discoveries suggest that "this site honours Zeus and two divine sons.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] The term *Hellenization* was coined by the German historian Johann Gustav Droysen to denote the spread of Greek language, culture, and population into the former Persian empire after Alexander's conquest.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] This process can be seen in such great Hellenistic cities as Alexandria, Antioch and Seleucia (south of modern Baghdad).
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] Alexander sought to insert Greek elements into Persian culture and to hybridize Greek and Persian culture, homogenizing the populations of Asia and Europe.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] Although his successors explicitly rejected such policies, Hellenization occurred throughout the region, accompanied by a distinct and opposite 'Orientalization' of the successor states.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] The core of the Hellenistic culture promulgated by the conquests was essentially Athenian.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] The close association of men from across Greece in Alexander's army directly led to the emergence of the largely Attic-based "koine", or "common" Greek dialect.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] Koine spread throughout the Hellenistic world, becoming the lingua franca of Hellenistic lands, and eventually the ancestor of modern Greek.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] Furthermore, town planning, education, local government, and art current in the Hellenistic period were all based on Classical Greek ideals, evolving into distinct new forms commonly grouped as Hellenistic.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] Also, the New Testament was written in the Koine Greek language.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] Aspects of Hellenistic culture were still evident in the traditions of the Byzantine Empire in the mid-15th century.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] Some of the most pronounced effects of Hellenization can be seen in Afghanistan and India, in the region of the relatively late-rising Greco-Bactrian Kingdom (250–125 BC) (in modern Afghanistan, Pakistan, and Tajikistan) and the Indo-Greek Kingdom (180 BC – 10 AD) in modern Afghanistan and India.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] On the Silk Road trade routes, Hellenistic culture hybridized with Iranian and Buddhist cultures.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] The resulting syncretism known as Greco-Buddhism influenced the development of Buddhism and created a culture of Greco-Buddhist art.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] These Greco-Buddhist kingdoms sent some of the first Buddhist missionaries to China, Sri Lanka and Hellenistic Asia and Europe (Greco-Buddhist monasticism).
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] Some of the first and most influential figurative portrayals of The Buddha appeared at this time, perhaps modelled on Greek statues of Apollo in the Greco-Buddhist style.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] One Greek king, Menander I, probably became Buddhist, and was immortalized in Buddhist literature as 'Milinda'.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] The process of Hellenization also spurred trade between the east and west.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] 'Greek astronomical treatise') and Paulisa Siddhanta texts depict the influence of Greek astronomical ideas on Indian astronomy.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] Following the conquests of Alexander the Great in the east, Hellenistic influence on Indian art was far-reaching.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] In architecture, a few examples of the Ionic order can be found as far as Pakistan with the Jandial temple near Taxila.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] Several examples of capitals displaying Ionic influences can be seen as far as Patna, especially with the Pataliputra capital, dated to the 3rd century BC.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] The Corinthian order is also heavily represented in the art of Gandhara, especially through Indo-Corinthian capitals.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] Alexander and his exploits were admired by many Romans, especially generals, who wanted to associate themselves with his achievements.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] Polybius began his *Histories* by reminding Romans of Alexander's achievements, and thereafter Roman leaders saw him as a role model.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] Pompey the Great adopted the epithet "Magnus" and even Alexander's anastole-type haircut, and searched the conquered lands of the east for Alexander's 260-year-old cloak, which he then wore as a sign of greatness.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] Julius Caesar dedicated a Lysippean equestrian bronze statue, but replaced Alexander's head with his own, while Octavian visited Alexander's tomb in Alexandria and temporarily changed his seal from a sphinx to Alexander's profile.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] The emperor Trajan also admired Alexander, as did Nero and Caracalla.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] The Macriani, a Roman family that in the person of Macrinus briefly ascended to the imperial throne, kept images of Alexander on their persons, either on jewellery or embroidered into their clothes.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] On the other hand, some Roman writers, particularly Republican figures, used Alexander as a cautionary tale of how autocratic tendencies can be kept in check by the values of the Roman Republic.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] Alexander was used by these writers as an example of ruler values such as *amicitia* (friendship) and *clementia* (clemency), but also *iracundia* (anger) and *cupiditas gloriae* (over-desire for glory).
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] Emperor Julian in his satire called "The Caesars", describes a contest between the previous Roman emperors, with Alexander the Great called in as an extra contestant, in the presence of the assembled gods.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] The Itinerarium Alexandri is a 4th-century Latin description of Alexander the Great's campaigns.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] Julius Caesar went to serve his quaestorship in Hispania after his wife's funeral, in the spring or early summer of 69 BC.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] While there, he encountered a statue of Alexander the Great, and realised with dissatisfaction that he was now at an age when Alexander had the world at his feet, while he had achieved comparatively little.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] Pompey posed as the "new Alexander" since he was his boyhood hero.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] After Caracalla concluded his campaign against the Alamanni, it became evident that he was inordinately preoccupied with Alexander the Great.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] He began openly mimicking Alexander in his personal style.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] In planning his invasion of the Parthian Empire, Caracalla decided to arrange 16,000 of his men in Macedonian-style phalanxes, despite the Roman army having made the phalanx an obsolete tactical formation.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] The historian Christopher Matthew mentions that the term *Phalangarii* has two possible meanings, both with military connotations.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] As a consequence, the *Phalangarii* of Legio II Parthica may not have been pikemen, but rather standard battle line troops or possibly *Triarii*.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] Caracalla's mania for Alexander went so far that Caracalla visited Alexandria while preparing for his Persian invasion and persecuted philosophers of the Aristotelian school based on a legend that Aristotle had poisoned Alexander.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] This was a sign of Caracalla's increasingly erratic behaviour.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] But this mania for Alexander, strange as it was, was overshadowed by subsequent events in Alexandria.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] In AD 39, Caligula performed a spectacular stunt by ordering a temporary floating bridge to be built using ships as pontoons, stretching for over two miles from the resort of Baiae to the neighbouring port of Puteoli.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] It was said that the bridge was to rival the Persian king Xerxes' pontoon bridge crossing of the Hellespont.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] Caligula, who could not swim, then proceeded to ride his favourite horse Incitatus across, wearing the breastplate of Alexander the Great.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] This act was in defiance of a prediction by Tiberius's soothsayer Thrasyllus of Mendes that Caligula had "no more chance of becoming emperor than of riding a horse across the Bay of Baiae".
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] The diffusion of Greek culture and language cemented by Alexander's conquests in West Asia and North Africa served as a "precondition" for the later Roman expansion into these territories and entire basis for the Byzantine Empire, according to Errington.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] Alexander wrote and received numerous letters, but no originals survive.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] A few official letters addressed to the Greek cities survive in copies inscribed in stone and the content of others is sometimes reported in historical sources.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] These only occasionally quote the letters and it is an open question how reliable such quotations are.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] Several fictitious letters, some perhaps based on actual letters, made their way into the *Romance* tradition.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] Many of the legends about Alexander derive from his own lifetime, probably encouraged by Alexander himself.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] His court historian Callisthenes portrayed the sea in Cilicia as drawing back from him in proskynesis.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] Writing shortly after Alexander's death, Onesicritus invented a tryst between Alexander and Thalestris, queen of the mythical Amazons.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] In the first centuries after Alexander's death, probably in Alexandria, a quantity of the legendary material coalesced into a text known as the *Alexander Romance*, later falsely ascribed to Callisthenes and therefore known as *Pseudo-Callisthenes*.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] This text underwent over one hundred recensions, translations, and derivations throughout the Islamic and European worlds in premodern times, containing many dubious stories, and was translated into twenty-five languages, for example Middle Persian, Syriac and Arabic.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] Alexander the Great's accomplishments and legacy have been depicted in many cultures.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] Alexander has featured in both high and popular culture, beginning from his own era to the present day.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] The *Alexander Romance*, in particular, has had a significant impact on portrayals of Alexander in later cultures, from Persian to medieval European, to modern Greek.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] Alexander features prominently in modern Greek folklore, more than any other ancient figure.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] The colloquial form of his name in modern Greek ("O Megalexandros") is a household name, and he is the only ancient hero to appear in the Karagiozis shadow play.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] One well-known fable among Greek seamen involves a solitary mermaid who would grasp a ship's prow during a storm and ask the captain, "Is King Alexander alive?" The answer should be "He is alive and well and rules the world!" causing the mermaid to vanish and the sea to calm.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] Any other answer would cause the mermaid to turn into a raging Gorgon who would drag the ship to the bottom of the sea, all hands aboard.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] In pre-Islamic Middle Persian (Zoroastrian) literature, Alexander is referred to by the epithet *gujastak*, meaning "accursed", and is accused of destroying temples and burning the sacred texts of Zoroastrianism.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] In Islamic Persia, under the influence of the *Alexander Romance* (in Persian: اسکندرنامه *Iskandarnameh*), a more positive portrayal of Alexander emerges.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] Firdausi's *Shahnameh* ("The Book of Kings") includes Alexander in a line of legitimate Persian shahs, a mythical figure who explored the far reaches of the world in search of the Fountain of Youth.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] In the *Shahnameh*, Alexander's first journey is to Mecca to pray at the Kaaba.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] Alexander was depicted as performing a Hajj (pilgrimage to Mecca) many times in subsequent Islamic art and literature.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] Later Persian writers associate him with philosophy, portraying him at a symposium with figures such as Socrates, Plato and Aristotle, in search of immortality.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] The figure of Dhu al-Qarnayn (Arabic: ذو القرنين; lit.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] 'The Two-Horned One') is believed by the majority of modern researchers of the Qur'an as well as Islamic commentators to be a reference to Alexander.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] The figure is also believed by scholars to be based on later legends of Alexander.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] In this tradition, he was a heroic figure who built a wall to defend against the nations of Gog and Magog.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] He also travelled the known world in search of the Water of Life and Immortality, eventually becoming a prophet.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] The Syriac version of the *Alexander Romance* portrays him as an ideal Christian world conqueror who prayed to "the one true God".
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] In Egypt, Alexander was portrayed as the son of Nectanebo II, the last pharaoh before the Persian conquest.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] His defeat of Darius was depicted as Egypt's salvation, "proving" Egypt was still ruled by an Egyptian.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] According to Josephus, Alexander was shown the Book of Daniel when he entered Jerusalem, which described a mighty Greek king who would conquer the Persian Empire.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] This is cited as a reason for sparing Jerusalem.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] In Hindi and Urdu, the name "Sikandar", derived from the Persian name for Alexander, denotes a rising young talent, and the Delhi Sultanate ruler Alauddin Khalji stylized himself as "Sikandar-i-Sani" (the Second Alexander the Great).
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] In medieval Europe, Alexander the Great was revered as a member of the Nine Worthies; a group of heroes whose lives were believed to encapsulate all the ideal qualities of chivalry.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] During the first Italian campaign of the French Revolutionary Wars, in a question from Bourrienne, asking whether he gave his preference to Alexander or Caesar, Napoleon said that he places Alexander The Great in the first rank, the main reason being his campaign on Asia.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] Apart from a few inscriptions and fragments, texts written by people who actually knew Alexander or who gathered information from men who served with Alexander were all lost.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] Contemporaries who wrote accounts of his life included Alexander's campaign historian Callisthenes, Alexander's generals; Ptolemy and Nearchus, Aristobulus, a junior officer on the campaigns, and Onesicritus, Alexander's chief helmsman.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] Their works are lost, but later works based on these original sources have survived.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] The earliest of these is Diodorus Siculus (1st century BC), followed by Quintus Curtius Rufus (mid-to-late 1st century AD), Arrian (1st to 2nd century AD), the biographer Plutarch (1st to 2nd century AD), and finally Justin, whose work dated as late as the 4th century.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/alexander-the-great-p02] Of these, Arrian is generally considered the most reliable, given that he used Ptolemy and Aristobulus as his sources, closely followed by Diodorus.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Three centuries after the decline of Mycenaean Greece during the Bronze Age collapse, Greek urban poleis began to form in the 8th century BC, ushering in the Archaic period and the colonization of the Mediterranean Basin.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] This was followed by the age of Classical Greece, from the Greco-Persian Wars to the death of Alexander the Great in 323 BC, and which included the Golden Age of Athens and the Peloponnesian War between Athens and Sparta.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] The unification of Greece by Macedon under Philip II and subsequent conquest of the Achaemenid Empire by Alexander the Great spread Hellenistic civilization across the Middle East.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] The Hellenistic period is considered to have ended in 30 BC, when the last Hellenistic kingdom, Ptolemaic Egypt, was annexed by the Roman Republic.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Classical Greek culture, especially philosophy, had a powerful influence on ancient Rome, which carried a version of it throughout the Mediterranean and much of Europe.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] For this reason, Classical Greece is generally considered the cradle of Western civilization, the seminal culture from which the modern West derives many of its founding archetypes and ideas in politics, philosophy, science, and art.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Classical antiquity in the Mediterranean region is commonly considered to have begun in the 8th century BC (around the time of the earliest recorded poetry of Homer) and ended in the 6th century AD.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Classical antiquity in Greece was preceded by the Greek Dark Ages (c.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] 800 BC), archaeologically characterised by the protogeometric and geometric styles of designs on pottery.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Following the Dark Ages was the Archaic period, beginning around the 8th century BC, which saw early developments in Greek culture and society leading to the Classical period from the Persian invasion of Greece in 480 BC until the death of Alexander the Great in 323 BC.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] The Classical period is characterized by a "classical" style, i.e. one which was considered exemplary by later observers, most famously in the Parthenon of Athens.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Politically, the Classical period was dominated by Athens and the Delian League during the 5th century, but displaced by Spartan hegemony during the early 4th century BC, before power shifted to Thebes and the Boeotian League and finally to the League of Corinth led by Macedon.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] This period was shaped by the Greco-Persian Wars, the Peloponnesian War, and the Rise of Macedon.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Following the Classical period was the Hellenistic period (323–146 BC), during which Greek culture and power expanded into the Near East from the death of Alexander until the Roman conquest.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Roman Greece is usually counted from the Roman victory over the Corinthians at the Battle of Corinth in 146 BC to the establishment of Byzantium by Constantine as the capital of the Roman Empire in 330 AD.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Finally, Late Antiquity refers to the period of Christianization during the later 4th to early 6th centuries AD, consummated by the closure of the Academy of Athens by Justinian I in 529.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] The historical period of ancient Greece is unique in world history as the first period attested directly in comprehensive, narrative historiography, while earlier ancient history or protohistory is known from much more fragmentary documents such as annals, king lists, and pragmatic epigraphy.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Herodotus is widely known as the "father of history": his *Histories* are eponymous of the entire field.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Written between the 450s and 420s BC, Herodotus' work reaches about a century into the past, discussing 6th-century BC historical figures such as Darius I of Persia, Cambyses II and Psamtik III, and alluding to some 8th-century BC persons such as Candaules.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] The accuracy of Herodotus' works is debated.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Herodotus was succeeded by authors such as Thucydides, Xenophon, Demosthenes, Plato and Aristotle.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Most were either Athenian or pro-Athenian, which is why far more is known about the history and politics of Athens than of many other cities.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Their scope is further limited by a focus on political, military and diplomatic history, ignoring economic and social history.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] The archaic period, lasting approximately from 800 to 500 BC, saw the culmination of political and social developments which had begun in the Greek Dark Age, with the *polis* (city-state) becoming the most important unit of political organisation in Greece.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] The absence of powerful states in Greece after the collapse of Mycenaean power, and the geography of Greece, where many settlements were separated from their neighbours by mountainous terrain, encouraged the development of small independent city-states.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Several Greek states saw tyrants rise to power in this period, most famously at Corinth from 657 BC.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] The period also saw the founding of Greek colonies around the Mediterranean, with Euboean settlements at Al-Mina in the east as early as 800 BC, and Ischia in the west by 775.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Increasing contact with non-Greek peoples in this period, especially in the Near East, inspired developments in art and architecture, the adoption of coinage, and the development of the Greek alphabet.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Athens developed its democratic system over the course of the archaic period.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Already in the 7th century, the right of all citizen men to attend the assembly appears to have been established.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] After a failed coup led by Cylon of Athens around 636 BC, Draco was appointed to establish a code of laws in 621.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] This failed to reduce the political tension between the poor and the elites, and in 594 Solon was given the authority to enact another set of reforms, which attempted to balance the power of the rich and the poor.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] In the middle of the 6th century, Pisistratus established himself as a tyrant, and after his death in 527 his son Hippias inherited his position; by the end of the 6th century he had been overthrown, and Cleisthenes carried out further democratising reforms.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] In Sparta, a political system with two kings, a council of elders, and five ephors developed over the course of the 8th and 7th centuries.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] According to Spartan tradition, this constitution was established by the legendary lawgiver Lycurgus.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Over the course of the First Messenian War and Second Messenian War, Sparta subjugated the neighbouring region of Messenia, enserfing the population.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] In the 6th century, Greek city-states began to develop formal relationships with one another, where previously individual rulers had relied on personal relationships with the elites of other cities.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Towards the end of the Archaic period, Sparta began to build a series of alliances, the Peloponnesian League, with cities including Corinth, Elis, and Megara, isolating Messenia and reinforcing Sparta's position against Argos, the other major power in the Peloponnese.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Other alliances in the 6th century included those between Elis and Heraea in the Peloponnese; and between the Greek colony Sybaris in southern Italy, its allies, and the Serdaioi.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] In 499 BC, the Ionian city-states under Persian rule rebelled against their Persian-supported tyrant rulers.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Supported by troops sent from Athens and Eretria, they advanced as far as Sardis and burnt the city before being driven back by a Persian counterattack.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] The revolt continued until 494, when the rebelling Ionians were defeated.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Darius did not forget that Athens had assisted the Ionian revolt, and in 490 he assembled an armada to retaliate.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Though heavily outnumbered, the Athenians—supported by their Plataean allies—defeated the Persian hordes at the Battle of Marathon, and the Persian fleet turned tail.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Ten years later, a second invasion was launched by Darius' son Xerxes.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] The city-states of northern and central Greece submitted to the Persian forces without resistance, but a coalition of 31 Greek city-states, including Athens and Sparta, determined to resist the Persian invaders.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] At the same time, Greek Sicily was invaded by a Carthaginian force.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] The Persians were decisively defeated at sea by a primarily Athenian naval force at the Battle of Salamis, and on land in 479 BC at the Battle of Plataea.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] The alliance against Persia continued, initially led by the Spartan Pausanias but from 477 by Athens, and by 460 Persia had been driven out of the Aegean.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] During this long campaign, the Delian League gradually transformed from a defensive alliance of Greek states into an Athenian empire, as Athens' growing naval power intimidated the other league states.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Athens ended its campaigns against Persia in 450, after a disastrous defeat in Egypt in 454, and the death of Cimon in action against the Persians on Cyprus in 450.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] As the Athenian fight against the Persian empire waned, conflict grew between Athens and Sparta.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Suspicious of the increasing Athenian power funded by the Delian League, Sparta offered aid to reluctant members of the League to rebel against Athenian domination.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] These tensions were exacerbated in 462 BC when Athens sent a force to aid Sparta in overcoming a helot revolt, but this aid was rejected by the Spartans.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] In the 450s, Athens took control of Boeotia, and won victories over Aegina and Corinth.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] However, Athens failed to win a decisive victory, and in 447 lost Boeotia again.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Athens and Sparta signed the Thirty Years' Peace in the winter of 446/445, ending the conflict.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Despite the treaty, Athenian relations with Sparta declined again in the 430s, and in 431 BC the Peloponnesian War began.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] The first phase of the war saw a series of fruitless annual invasions of Attica by Sparta, while Athens successfully fought the Corinthian empire in northwest Greece and defended its own empire, despite a plague which killed the leading Athenian statesman Pericles.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] The war turned after Athenian victories led by Cleon at Pylos and Sphakteria, and Sparta sued for peace, but the Athenians rejected the proposal.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] The Athenian failure to regain control of Boeotia at Delium and Brasidas' successes in northern Greece in 424 improved Sparta's position after Sphakteria.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] After the deaths of Cleon and Brasidas, the strongest proponents of war on each side, a peace treaty was negotiated in 421 by the Athenian general Nicias.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] In 418 BC allied forces of Athens and Argos were defeated by Sparta at Mantinea.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] In 415 Athens launched an ambitious naval expedition to dominate Sicily; the expedition ended in disaster at the harbor of Syracuse, with almost the entire army killed, and the ships destroyed.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Soon after the Athenian defeat in Syracuse, Athens' Ionian allies began to rebel against the Delian league, while Persia began to once again involve itself in Greek affairs on the Spartan side.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Initially the Athenian position continued relatively strong, with important victories at Cyzicus in 410 and Arginusae in 406.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] However, in 405 the Spartan Lysander defeated Athens in the Battle of Aegospotami, and began to blockade Athens' harbour; driven by hunger, Athens sued for peace, agreeing to surrender their fleet and join the Spartan-led Peloponnesian League.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Following the Athenian surrender, Sparta installed an oligarchic regime, the Thirty Tyrants, in Athens, one of a number of Spartan-backed oligarchies which rose to power after the Peloponnesian war.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Spartan predominance did not last: after only a year, the Thirty had been overthrown.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] The first half of the 4th century saw the major Greek states attempt to dominate the mainland; none were successful, and their resulting weakness led to a power vacuum which was eventually filled by Macedon under Philip II and then Alexander the Great.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] In the immediate aftermath of the Peloponnesian war, Sparta attempted to extend their own power, leading Argos, Athens, Corinth, and Thebes to join against them.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Aiming to prevent any single Greek state gaining the dominance that would allow it to challenge Persia, the Persian king initially joined the alliance against Sparta, before imposing the Peace of Antalcidas ("King's Peace") which restored Persia's control over the Anatolian Greeks.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] By 371 BC, Thebes was in the ascendancy, defeating Sparta at the Battle of Leuctra, killing the Spartan king Cleombrotus I, and invading Laconia.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Further Theban successes against Sparta in 369 led to Messenia gaining independence; Sparta never recovered from the loss of Messenia's fertile land and the helot workforce it provided.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] The rising power of Thebes led Sparta and Athens to join forces; in 362 they were defeated by Thebes at the Battle of Mantinea.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] In the aftermath of Mantinea, none of the major Greek states were able to dominate.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Though Thebes had won the battle, their general Epaminondas was killed, and they spent the following decades embroiled in wars with their neighbours; Athens, meanwhile, saw its second naval alliance, formed in 377, collapse in the mid-350s.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] The power vacuum in Greece after the Battle of Mantinea was filled by Macedon, under Philip II, starting from the battle of Crocus field.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] In 338 BC, he defeated a Greek alliance at the Battle of Chaeronea, and subsequently formed the League of Corinth.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Philip planned to lead the League to invade Persia, but was murdered in 336 BC.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] His son Alexander the Great was left to fulfill his father's ambitions.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] After campaigns against Macedon's western and northern enemies, and those Greek states that had broken from the League of Corinth following the death of Philip, Alexander began his campaign against Persia in 334 BC.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] He conquered Persia, defeating Darius III at the Battle of Issus in 333 BC, and after the Battle of Gaugamela in 331 BC proclaimed himself king of Asia.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] From 329 BC he led expeditions to Bactria and then India; further plans to invade Arabia and North Africa were halted by his death in 323 BC.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] The period from the death of Alexander the Great in 323 BC until the death of Cleopatra, the last Macedonian ruler of Egypt, is known as the Hellenistic period.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] In the early part of this period, a new form of kingship developed based on Macedonian and Near Eastern traditions.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] The first Hellenistic kings were previously Alexander's generals, and took power in the period following his death, though they were not part of existing royal lineages and lacked historic claims to the territories they controlled.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] In the early part of the Hellenistic period, the exact borders of the Hellenistic kingdoms were not settled.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Antigonus attempted to expand his territory by attacking the other successor kingdoms until they joined against him, and he was killed at the Battle of Ipsus in 301 BC.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] His son Demetrius spent many years in Seleucid captivity, and his son, Antigonus II, only reclaimed the Macedonian throne around 276.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Meanwhile, the Seleucid kingdom gave up territory in the east to the Indian king Chandragupta Maurya in exchange for war elephants, and later lost large parts of Persia to the Parthian Empire.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] By the mid-3rd century, the kingdoms of Alexander's successors was mostly stable, though there continued to be disputes over border areas.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] The great capitals of Hellenistic culture were Alexandria in the Ptolemaic Kingdom and Antioch in the Seleucid Empire.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] The conquests of Alexander had numerous consequences for the Greek city-states.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] It greatly widened the horizons of the Greeks and led to a steady emigration of the young and ambitious to the new Greek empires in the east.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Many Greeks migrated to Alexandria, Antioch and the many other new Hellenistic cities founded in Alexander's wake, as far away as present-day Afghanistan and Pakistan, where the Greco-Bactrian Kingdom and the Indo-Greek Kingdom survived until the end of the 1st century BC.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Some city-states within Greece formed themselves into two major leagues; the Achaean League (including Corinth and Argos) and the Aetolian League.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] For much of the period until the Roman conquest, these leagues were at war, often participating in the conflicts between the Diadochi's successor states to Alexander's empire.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] The Antigonid Kingdom became involved in a war with the Roman Republic in the late 3rd century.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Although the First Macedonian War was inconclusive, the Romans, in typical fashion, continued to fight Macedon until it was completely absorbed into the Roman Republic (by 149 BC).
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] In the east, the unwieldy Seleucid Empire gradually disintegrated, although a rump survived until 64 BC, whilst the Ptolemaic Kingdom continued in Egypt until 30 BC when it too was conquered by the Romans.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] The Aetolian league grew wary of Roman involvement in Greece, and sided with the Seleucids in the Roman–Seleucid War; when the Romans were victorious, the league was effectively absorbed into the Republic.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Although the Achaean league outlasted both the Aetolian league and Macedon, it was also soon defeated and absorbed by the Romans in 146 BC, bringing Greek independence to an end.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] The Greek peninsula came under Roman rule during the 146 BC conquest of Greece after the Battle of Corinth.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Macedonia became a Roman province while southern Greece came under the surveillance of Macedonia's prefect; however, some Greek *poleis* managed to maintain a partial independence and avoid taxation.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] The Aegean Islands were added to this territory in 133 BC.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Athens and other Greek cities revolted in 88 BC, and the peninsula was crushed by the Roman general Sulla.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] The Roman civil wars devastated the land even further, until Augustus organized the peninsula as the province of Achaea in 27 BC.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Greece was a key eastern province of the Roman Empire, as the Roman culture had long been in fact Greco-Roman.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] The Greek language served as a *lingua franca* in the East and in Italy, and many Greek intellectuals such as Galen would perform most of their work in Rome.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] The territory of Greece is mountainous, and as a result, ancient Greece consisted of many smaller regions, each with its own dialect, cultural peculiarities, and identity.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Regionalism and regional conflicts were prominent features of ancient Greece.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Cities tended to be located in valleys between mountains, or on coastal plains, and dominated a certain area around them.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] In the south lay the Peloponnese, consisting of the regions of Laconia (southeast), Messenia (southwest), Elis (west), Achaia (north), Korinthia (northeast), Argolis (east), and Arcadia (center).
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] These names survive to the present day as regional units of modern Greece, though with somewhat different boundaries.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Mainland Greece to the north, nowadays known as Central Greece, consisted of Aetolia and Acarnania in the west, Locris, Doris, and Phocis in the center, while in the east lay Boeotia, Attica, and Megaris.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Northeast lay Thessaly, while Epirus lay to the northwest.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Epirus stretched from the Ambracian Gulf in the south to the Ceraunian Mountains and the Aoos river in the north, and consisted of Chaonia (north), Molossia (center), and Thesprotia (south).
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] In the northeast corner was Macedonia, originally consisting Lower Macedonia and its regions, such as Emathia (Macedonia), Pieria, and Bottiaea, and later Almopia, Amphaxitis.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] The original capital of Macedon was Aigai and then moved to Pella in the 4th century BC.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] To the north of Macedonia lay various non-Greek peoples such as the Paeonians due north, the Thracians to the northeast, and the Illyrians, with whom the Macedonians were frequently in conflict, to the northwest.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Chalcidice was settled early on by southern Greek colonists and was considered part of the Greek world, while from the late 2nd millennium BC substantial Greek settlement also occurred on the eastern shores of the Aegean, in Anatolia.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] This was not simply for trade, but also to found settlements.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] These Greek colonies were not, as Roman colonies were, dependent on their mother-city, but were independent city-states in their own right.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Greeks settled outside of Greece in two distinct ways.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] The first was in permanent settlements founded by Greeks, which formed as independent poleis.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] The second form was in what historians refer to as *emporia*; trading posts which were occupied by both Greeks and non-Greeks and which were primarily concerned with the manufacture and sale of goods.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Examples of this latter type of settlement are found at Al Mina in the east and Pithekoussai in the west.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] From around 750 to 500 BC, Greeks settled colonies in all directions.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] To the east, the Aegean coast of Asia Minor was colonized first, followed by Cyprus and the coasts of Thrace, the Sea of Marmara and the south coast of the Black Sea.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Eventually, Greek colonization reached as far northeast as present-day Ukraine and Russia (Taganrog).
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] To the west the coasts of Illyria, Southern Italy (called "Magna Graecia") were settled, followed by Southern France, Corsica, and even eastern Spain.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Greek colonies were also founded in Egypt and Libya.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Modern Syracuse, Naples, Marseille and Istanbul had their beginnings as the Greek colonies Syracusae (Συράκουσαι), Neapolis (Νεάπολις), Massalia (Μασσαλία) and Byzantion (Βυζάντιον).
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] These colonies played an important role in the spread of Greek influence throughout Europe and also aided in the establishment of long-distance trading networks between the Greek city-states, boosting the economy of ancient Greece.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Ancient Greece consisted of several hundred relatively independent city-states (*poleis*).
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] This was a situation unlike that in most other contemporary societies, which were either tribal or kingdoms ruling over relatively large territories.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Undoubtedly, the geography of Greece—divided and sub-divided by hills, mountains, and rivers—contributed to the fragmentary nature of ancient Greece.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] On the one hand, the ancient Greeks had no doubt that they were "one people"; they had the same religion, same basic culture, and same language.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Furthermore, the Greeks were very aware of their tribal origins; Herodotus was able to extensively categorise the city-states by tribe.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Yet, although these higher-level relationships existed, they seem to have rarely had a major role in Greek politics.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] The independence of the *poleis* was fiercely defended; unification was something rarely contemplated by the ancient Greeks.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Even when, during the second Persian invasion of Greece, a group of city-states allied themselves to defend Greece, the vast majority of *poleis* remained neutral, and after the Persian defeat, the allies quickly returned to infighting.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Thus, the major peculiarities of the ancient Greek political system were its fragmented nature (and that this does not particularly seem to have tribal origin), and the particular focus on urban centers within otherwise tiny states.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] The peculiarities of the Greek system are further evidenced by the colonies that they set up throughout the Mediterranean, which, though they might count a certain Greek *polis* as their 'mother' (and remain sympathetic to her), were completely independent of the founding city.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Inevitably smaller *poleis* might be dominated by larger neighbors, but conquest or direct rule by another city-state appears to have been quite rare.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Instead the *poleis* grouped themselves into leagues, membership of which was in a constant state of flux.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Later in the Classical period, the leagues would become fewer and larger, be dominated by one city (particularly Athens, Sparta and Thebes); and often *poleis* would be compelled to join under threat of war (or as part of a peace treaty).
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Even after Philip II of Macedon conquered the heartlands of ancient Greece, he did not attempt to annex the territory or unify it into a new province, but compelled most of the *poleis* to join his own Corinthian League.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Initially many Greek city-states seem to have been petty kingdoms; there was often a city official carrying some residual, ceremonial functions of the king (*basileus*), e.g., the *archon basileus* in Athens.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] However, by the Archaic period and the first historical consciousness, most had already become aristocratic oligarchies.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] It is unclear exactly how this change occurred.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] For instance, in Athens, the kingship had been reduced to a hereditary, lifelong chief magistracy (*archon*) by c.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] 1050 BC; by 753 BC this had become a decennial, elected archonship, and finally an annually elected archonship by 683 BC.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Through each stage, more power would have been transferred to the aristocracy as a whole, and away from a single individual.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Inevitably, the domination of politics and concomitant aggregation of wealth by small groups of families was apt to cause social unrest in many *poleis*.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] In many cities a tyrant (not in the modern sense of repressive autocracies), would at some point seize control and govern according to their own will; often a populist agenda would help sustain them in power.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] In a system wracked with class conflict, government by a 'strongman' was often the best solution.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Athens fell under a tyranny in the second half of the 6th century BC.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] When this tyranny was ended, the Athenians founded the world's first democracy as a radical solution to prevent the aristocracy regaining power.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] A citizens' assembly (the *Ecclesia*), for the discussion of city policy, had existed since the reforms of Draco in 621 BC; all citizens were permitted to attend after the reforms of Solon (early 6th century), but the poorest citizens could not address the assembly or run for office.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] With the establishment of the democracy, the assembly became the *de jure* mechanism of government; all citizens had equal privileges in the assembly.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] However, non-citizens, such as metics (foreigners living in Athens) or slaves, had no political rights at all.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] After the rise of democracy in Athens, other city-states founded democracies.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] However, many retained more traditional forms of government.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] As so often in other matters, Sparta was a notable exception to the rest of Greece, ruled through the whole period by not one, but two hereditary monarchs.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] The Kings of Sparta belonged to the Agiads and the Eurypontids, descendants respectively of Eurysthenes and Procles.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Both dynasties' founders were believed to be twin sons of Aristodemus, a Heraclid ruler.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] However, the powers of these kings were held in check by both a council of elders (the *Gerousia*) and magistrates specifically appointed to watch over the kings (the *Ephors*).
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Only free, land-owning, native-born men could be citizens entitled to the full protection of the law in a city-state.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] In most city-states, unlike the situation in Rome, social prominence did not allow special rights.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Sometimes families controlled public religious functions, but this ordinarily did not give any extra power in the government.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] In Athens, the population was divided into four social classes based on wealth.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] People could change classes if they made more money.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] In Sparta, all male citizens were called *homoioi*, meaning "peers".
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] However, Spartan kings, who served as the city-state's dual military and religious leaders, came from two families.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Women in Ancient Greece appear to have primarily performed domestic tasks, managed households, and borne and reared children.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Slaves had the right to have a family and own property, subject to their master's goodwill and permission, but they had no political rights.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] By 600 BC, chattel slavery had spread in Greece.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] By the 5th century BC, slaves made up one-third of the total population in some city-states.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Between 40 and 80% of the population of Classical Athens were slaves.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Slaves outside of Sparta almost never revolted because they were made up of too many nationalities and were too scattered to organize.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] However, unlike later Western culture, the ancient Greeks did not think in terms of race.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Most families owned slaves as household servants and laborers, and even poor families might have owned a few slaves.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Owners were not allowed to beat or kill their slaves.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Owners often promised to free slaves in the future to encourage slaves to work hard.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Unlike in Rome, freedmen did not become citizens.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Instead, they were mixed into the population of *metics*, which included people from foreign countries or other city-states who were officially allowed to live in the state.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] These public slaves had a larger measure of independence than slaves owned by families, living on their own and performing specialized tasks.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] In Athens, public slaves were trained to look out for counterfeit coinage, while temple slaves acted as servants of the temple's deity and Scythian slaves were employed in Athens as a police force corralling citizens to political functions.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Sparta had a special type of slaves called *helots*.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Helots were Messenians enslaved en masse during the Messenian Wars by the state and assigned to families where they were forced to stay.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Helots raised food and did household chores so that women could concentrate on raising strong children while men could devote their time to training as hoplites.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Their masters treated them harshly, and helots revolted against their masters several times.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] In 370/369 BC, as a result of Epaminondas' liberation of Messenia from Spartan rule, the helot system there came to an end and the helots won their freedom.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] However, it persisted in Laconia until the 2nd century BC.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] For most of Greek history, education was private, except in Sparta.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] During the Hellenistic period, some city-states established public schools.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Only wealthy families could afford a teacher.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Boys learned how to read, write and quote literature.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] They also learned to sing and play one musical instrument and were trained as athletes for military service.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] They studied not for a job but to become an effective citizen.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Girls also learned to read, write and do simple arithmetic so they could manage the household.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] They almost never received education after childhood.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Boys went to school at the age of seven, or went to the barracks, if they lived in Sparta.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] The three types of teachings were: grammatistes for arithmetic, kitharistes for music and dancing, and Paedotribae for sports.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Boys from wealthy families attending the private school lessons were taken care of by a *paidagogos*, a household slave selected for this task who accompanied the boy during the day.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Classes were held in teachers' private houses and included reading, writing, mathematics, singing, and playing the lyre and flute.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] When the boy became 12 years old the schooling started to include sports such as wrestling, running, and throwing discus and javelin.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] In Athens, some older youths attended academy for the finer disciplines such as culture, sciences, music, and the arts.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] The schooling ended at age 18, followed by military training in the army usually for one or two years.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Some of Athens' greatest such schools included the Lyceum (the so-called Peripatetic school founded by Aristotle of Stageira) and the Platonic Academy (founded by Plato of Athens).
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] The education system of the wealthy ancient Greeks is also called Paideia.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] At its economic height in the 5th and 4th centuries BC, the free citizenry of Classical Greece represented perhaps the most prosperous society in the ancient world, some economic historians considering Greece one of the most advanced pre-industrial economies.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] In terms of wheat, wages reached an estimated 7–12 kg (15–26 lb) daily for an unskilled worker in urban Athens, 2–3 times the 3.75 kg (8.3 lb) of an unskilled rural labourer in Roman Egypt, though Greek farm incomes too were on average lower than those available to urban workers.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] At least in the Archaic period, the fragmentary nature of ancient Greece, with many competing city-states, increased the frequency of conflict but conversely limited the scale of warfare.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Unable to maintain professional armies, the city-states relied on their own citizens to fight.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] This inevitably reduced the potential duration of campaigns, as citizens would need to return to their own professions (especially in the case of, for example, farmers).
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Campaigns would therefore often be restricted to summer.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] When battles occurred, they were usually set piece and intended to be decisive.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Casualties were slight compared to later battles, rarely amounting to more than five percent of the losing side, but the slain often included the most prominent citizens and generals who led from the front.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] The scale and scope of warfare in ancient Greece changed dramatically as a result of the Greco-Persian Wars.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] To fight the enormous armies of the Achaemenid Empire was effectively beyond the capabilities of a single city-state.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] The eventual triumph of the Greeks was achieved by alliances of city-states (the exact composition changing over time), allowing the pooling of resources and division of labor.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Although alliances between city-states occurred before this time, nothing on this scale had been seen before.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] The rise of Athens and Sparta as pre-eminent powers during this conflict led directly to the Peloponnesian War, which saw further development of the nature of warfare, strategy and tactics.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Fought between leagues of cities dominated by Athens and Sparta, the increased manpower and financial resources increased the scale and allowed the diversification of warfare.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Set-piece battles during the Peloponnesian war proved indecisive and instead there was increased reliance on attritionary strategies, naval battles and blockades and sieges.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] These changes greatly increased the number of casualties and the disruption of Greek society.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Athens owned one of the largest war fleets in ancient Greece.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] It had over 200 triremes each powered by 170 oarsmen who were seated in 3 rows on each side of the ship.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] The city could afford such a large fleet—it had over 34,000 oarsmen—because it owned a lot of silver mines that were worked by slaves.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] According to Josiah Ober, Greek city-states faced approximately a one-in-three chance of destruction during the archaic and classical period.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Ancient Greek philosophy focused on the role of reason and inquiry.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] In many ways, it had an important influence on modern philosophy, as well as modern science.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Clear unbroken lines of influence lead from ancient Greek and Hellenistic philosophers, to medieval Muslim philosophers and Islamic scientists, to the European Renaissance and Enlightenment, to the secular sciences of the modern day.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Neither reason nor inquiry began with the ancient Greeks.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Defining the difference between the Greek quest for knowledge and the quests of the elder civilizations, such as the ancient Egyptians and Babylonians, has long been a topic of study by theorists of civilization.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] The first known philosophers of Greece were the pre-Socratics, who attempted to provide naturalistic, non-mythical descriptions of the world.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] They were followed by Socrates, one of the first philosophers based in Athens during its golden age whose ideas, despite being known by second-hand accounts instead of writings of his own, laid the basis of Western philosophy.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Socrates' disciple Plato, who wrote *The Republic* and established a radical difference between ideas and the concrete world, and Plato's disciple Aristotle, who wrote extensively about nature and ethics, are also immensely influential in Western philosophy to this day.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] The later Hellenistic philosophy, also originating in Greece, is defined by names such as Antisthenes (cynicism), Zeno of Citium (stoicism) and Plotinus (Neoplatonism).
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] The earliest Greek literature was poetry and was composed for performance rather than private consumption.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] The earliest Greek poet known is Homer, although he was certainly part of an existing tradition of oral poetry.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Homer's poetry, though it was developed around the same time that the Greeks developed writing, would have been composed orally; the first poet to certainly compose their work in writing was Archilochus, a lyric poet from the mid-7th century BC.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Tragedy developed around the end of the archaic period, taking elements from across the pre-existing genres of late archaic poetry.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Like poetry, Greek prose had its origins in the archaic period, and the earliest writers of Greek philosophy, history, and medical literature all date to the 6th century BC.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Prose first emerged as the writing style adopted by the presocratic philosophers Anaximander and Anaximenes—though Thales of Miletus, considered the first Greek philosopher, apparently wrote nothing.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Prose as a genre reached maturity in the classical era, and the major Greek prose genres—philosophy, history, rhetoric, and dialogue—developed in this period.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] The Hellenistic period saw the literary centre of the Greek world move from Athens, where it had been in the classical period, to Alexandria.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] At the same time, other Hellenistic kings such as the Antigonids and the Attalids were patrons of scholarship and literature, turning Pella and Pergamon respectively into cultural centres.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] It was thanks to this cultural patronage by Hellenistic kings, and especially the Museum at Alexandria, that so much ancient Greek literature has survived.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] The Library of Alexandria, part of the Museum, had the previously unenvisaged aim of collecting together copies of all known authors in Greek.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Almost all of the surviving non-technical Hellenistic literature is poetry, and Hellenistic poetry tended to be highly intellectual, blending different genres and traditions, and avoiding linear narratives.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] The Hellenistic period also saw a shift in the ways literature was consumed—while in the archaic and classical periods literature had typically been experienced in public performance, in the Hellenistic period it was more commonly read privately.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] At the same time, Hellenistic poets began to write for private, rather than public, consumption.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] With Octavian's victory at Actium in 31 BC, Rome began to become a major centre of Greek literature, as important Greek authors such as Strabo and Dionysius of Halicarnassus came to Rome.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] The period of greatest innovation in Greek literature under Rome was the "long second century" from approximately 80 AD to around 230 AD.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] This innovation was especially marked in prose, with the development of the novel and a revival of prominence for display oratory both dating to this period.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] In Ancient Greek society, music was ever-present and considered a fundamental component of civilisation.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] It was an important part of public religious worship, private ceremonies such as weddings and funerals, and household entertainment.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Men sang and played music at the symposium; both men and women sang at work; and children's games involved song and dance.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Ancient Greek music was primarily vocal, sung either by a solo singer or a chorus, and usually accompanied by an instrument; purely instrumental music was less common.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] The Greeks used stringed instruments, including lyres, harps, and lutes; and wind instruments, of which the most important was the *aulos*, a reed instrument.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Percussion instruments played a relatively unimportant role supporting stringed and wind instruments, and were used in certain religious cults.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Ancient Greek mathematics contributed many important developments to mathematics, including the basic rules of geometry, the idea of formal mathematical proof, and discoveries in number theory, mathematical analysis, applied mathematics, and approached close to establishing integral calculus.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] The discoveries of several Greek mathematicians, including Pythagoras, Euclid, and Archimedes, are still used in mathematical teaching today.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] The Greeks developed astronomy, which they treated as a branch of mathematics, to a highly sophisticated level.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] The first geometrical, three-dimensional models to explain the apparent motion of the planets were developed in the 4th century BC by Eudoxus of Cnidus and Callippus of Cyzicus.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Their younger contemporary Heraclides Ponticus proposed that the Earth rotates around its axis.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] In the 3rd century BC, Aristarchus of Samos was the first to suggest a heliocentric system.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Archimedes in his treatise The Sand Reckoner revives Aristarchus' hypothesis that *"the fixed stars and the Sun remain unmoved, while the Earth revolves about the Sun on the circumference of a circle"*.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Otherwise, only fragmentary descriptions of Aristarchus' idea survive.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Eratosthenes, using the angles of shadows created at widely separated regions, estimated the circumference of the Earth with great accuracy.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] In the 2nd century BC Hipparchus of Nicea made a number of contributions, including the first measurement of precession and the compilation of the first star catalog in which he proposed the modern system of apparent magnitudes.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] The Antikythera mechanism, a device for calculating the movements of planets, dates from about 80 BC and was the first ancestor of the astronomical computer.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] It was discovered in an ancient shipwreck off the Greek island of Antikythera, between Kythera and Crete.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] The device became famous for its use of a differential gear, previously believed to have been invented in the 16th century, and the miniaturization and complexity of its parts, comparable to a clock made in the 18th century.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] The original mechanism is displayed in the Bronze collection of the National Archaeological Museum of Athens, accompanied by a replica.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] The ancient Greeks also made important discoveries in the medical field.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Hippocrates was a physician of the Classical period, and is considered one of the most outstanding figures in the history of medicine.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] He is referred to as the "father of medicine" in recognition of his lasting contributions to the field as the founder of the Hippocratic school of medicine.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] This intellectual school revolutionized medicine in ancient Greece, establishing it as a discipline distinct from other fields that it had traditionally been associated with (notably theurgy and philosophy), thus making medicine a profession.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] The art of ancient Greece has exercised an enormous influence on the culture of many countries from ancient times to the present day, particularly in the areas of sculpture and architecture.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] In the West, the art of the Roman Empire was largely derived from Greek models.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] In the East, Alexander the Great's conquests initiated several centuries of exchange between Greek, Central Asian and Indian cultures, resulting in Greco-Buddhist art, with ramifications as far as Japan.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Following the Renaissance in Europe, the humanist aesthetic and the high technical standards of Greek art inspired generations of European artists.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Well into the 19th century, the classical tradition derived from Greece dominated the art of the Western world.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Religion was a central part of ancient Greek life.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Though the Greeks of different cities and tribes worshipped similar gods, religious practices were not uniform and the gods were thought of differently in different places.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] The Greeks were polytheistic, worshipping many gods, but as early as the 6th century BC a pantheon of twelve Olympians began to develop.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Greek religion was influenced by the practices of the Greeks' near eastern neighbours at least as early as the archaic period, and by the Hellenistic period this influence was seen in both directions.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] The most important religious act in ancient Greece was animal sacrifice, most commonly of sheep and goats.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Sacrifice was accompanied by public prayer, and prayer and hymns were themselves a major part of ancient Greek religious life.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] The civilization of ancient Greece has been immensely influential on language, politics, educational systems, philosophy, science, and the arts.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] It became the *Leitkultur* of the Roman Empire to the point of marginalizing native Italic traditions.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] Via the Roman Empire, Greek culture came to be foundational to Western culture in general.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greece] A modern revival of Classical Greek learning took place in the Neoclassicism movement in 18th- and 19th-century Europe and the Americas.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greek-language] Ancient Greek was the language of Homer and of fifth-century Athenian historians, playwrights, and philosophers.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greek-language] It has contributed many words to English vocabulary and has been a standard subject of study in educational institutions of the Western world since the Renaissance.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greek-language] This article primarily contains information about the Epic and Classical periods of the language, which are the best-attested periods and considered most typical of Ancient Greek.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greek-language] Ancient Greek comprised several dialects, such as Attic, Ionic, Doric, Aeolic, and Arcadocypriot; among them, Attic Greek became the basis of Koine Greek.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greek-language] Just like Koine is often included in Ancient Greek, conversely, Mycenaean Greek is usually treated separately and not always included in Ancient Greek – reflecting the fact that Greek in the first millennium BC is considered prototypical of Ancient Greek.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greek-language] Ancient Greek was a pluricentric language, divided into many dialects.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greek-language] The main dialect groups are Attic and Ionic, Aeolic, Arcadocypriot, and Doric, many of them with several subdivisions.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greek-language] Some dialects are found in standardized literary forms in literature, while others are attested only in inscriptions.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greek-language] There are also several historical forms.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greek-language] Homeric Greek is a literary form of Archaic Greek (derived primarily from Ionic and Aeolic) used in the epic poems, the *Iliad* and the *Odyssey*, and in later poems by other authors.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greek-language] Homeric Greek had significant differences in grammar and pronunciation from Classical Attic and other Classical-era dialects.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greek-language] The origins, early form and development of the Hellenic language family are not well understood because of a lack of contemporaneous evidence.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greek-language] Several theories exist about what Hellenic dialect groups may have existed between the divergence of early Greek-like speech from the common Proto-Indo-European language and the Classical period.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greek-language] They have the same general outline but differ in some of the detail.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greek-language] The only attested dialect from this period is Mycenaean Greek, but its relationship to the historical dialects and the historical circumstances of the times imply that the overall groups already existed in some form.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greek-language] Scholars assume that major Ancient Greek period dialect groups developed no later than 1120 BC, at the time of the Dorian invasions—and that their first appearances as precise alphabetic writing began in the 8th century BC.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greek-language] The invasion would not be "Dorian" unless the invaders had some cultural relationship to the historical Dorians.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greek-language] The invasion is known to have displaced population to the later Attic-Ionic regions, who regarded themselves as descendants of the population displaced by or contending with the Dorians.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greek-language] The Greeks of this period believed there were three major divisions of all Greek people – Dorians, Aeolians, and Ionians (including Athenians), each with their own defining and distinctive dialects.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greek-language] Allowing for their oversight of Arcadian, an obscure mountain dialect, and Cypriot, far from the center of Greek scholarship, this division of people and language is quite similar to the results of modern archaeological-linguistic investigation.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greek-language] (Southern Italy and Sicily) in the classical period.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greek-language] West vs. non-West Greek is the strongest-marked and earliest division, with non-West in subsets of Ionic-Attic (or Attic-Ionic) and Aeolic vs.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greek-language] Arcadocypriot, or Aeolic and Arcado-Cypriot vs.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greek-language] Arcadocypriot apparently descended more closely from the Mycenaean Greek of the Bronze Age.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greek-language] Boeotian Greek had come under a strong Northwest Greek influence, and can in some respects be considered a transitional dialect, as exemplified in the poems of the Boeotian poet Pindar who wrote in Doric with a small Aeolic admixture.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greek-language] Thessalian likewise had come under Northwest Greek influence, though to a lesser degree.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greek-language] Pamphylian Greek, spoken in a small area on the southwestern coast of Anatolia and little preserved in inscriptions, may be either a fifth major dialect group, or it is Mycenaean Greek overlaid by Doric, with a non-Greek native influence.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greek-language] Based on the conclusions drawn by several studies and findings such as Pella curse tablet, Emilio Crespo and most scholars suggest that ancient Macedonian was a Northwest Doric dialect, which shares isoglosses with its neighboring Thessalian dialects spoken in northeastern Thessaly.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greek-language] Some have also suggested an Aeolic Greek classification.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greek-language] For example, fragments of the works of the poet Sappho from the island of Lesbos are in Aeolian.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greek-language] Most of the dialect sub-groups listed above had further subdivisions, generally equivalent to a city-state and its surrounding territory, or to an island.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greek-language] Doric notably had several intermediate divisions as well, into Island Doric (including Cretan Doric), Southern Peloponnesus Doric (including Laconian, the dialect of Sparta), and Northern Peloponnesus Doric (including Corinthian).
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greek-language] All the groups were represented by colonies beyond Greece proper as well, and these colonies generally developed local characteristics, often under the influence of settlers or neighbors speaking different Greek dialects.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greek-language] After the conquests of Alexander the Great in the late 4th century BC, a new international dialect known as Koine or Common Greek developed, largely based on Attic Greek, but with influence from other dialects.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greek-language] This dialect slowly replaced most of the older dialects, although the Doric dialect has survived in the Tsakonian language, which is spoken in the region of modern Sparta.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greek-language] Doric has also passed down its aorist terminations into most verbs of Demotic Greek.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greek-language] By about the 6th century AD, the Koine had slowly metamorphosed into Medieval Greek.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greek-language] Phrygian is an extinct Indo-European language of West and Central Anatolia, which is regarded by current consensus to have been closely related to Greek.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greek-language] Among Indo-European branches with living descendants, Greek is often argued to have the closest genetic ties with Armenian (see also Graeco-Armenian) and Indo-Iranian languages (see Graeco-Aryan).
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greek-language] Ancient Greek differs from Proto-Indo-European (PIE) and other Indo-European languages in certain ways.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greek-language] In phonotactics, ancient Greek words could end only in a vowel or /n s r/; final stops were lost, as in γάλα "milk", compared with γάλακτος "of milk" (genitive).
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greek-language] The pronunciation of Ancient Greek was very different from that of Modern Greek.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greek-language] Ancient Greek had long and short vowels; many diphthongs; double and single consonants; voiced, voiceless, and aspirated stops; and a pitch accent.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greek-language] In Modern Greek, all vowels and consonants are short.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greek-language] Many vowels and diphthongs once pronounced distinctly are pronounced as /i/ (iotacism).
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greek-language] Some of the stops and glides in diphthongs have become fricatives, and the pitch accent has changed to a stress accent.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greek-language] Many of the changes took place in the Koine Greek period.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greek-language] The writing system of Modern Greek, however, does not reflect all pronunciation changes.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greek-language] The examples below represent Attic Greek in the 5th century BC.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greek-language] Ancient pronunciation cannot be reconstructed with certainty, but Greek from the period is well documented, and there is little disagreement among linguists as to the general nature of the sounds that the letters represent.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greek-language] /oː/ raised to [uː], probably by the 4th century BC.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greek-language] Greek, like all of the older Indo-European languages, is highly inflected.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greek-language] It is highly archaic in its preservation of Proto-Indo-European forms.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greek-language] In ancient Greek, nouns (including proper nouns) have five cases (nominative, genitive, dative, accusative, and vocative), three genders (masculine, feminine, and neuter), and three numbers (singular, dual, and plural).
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greek-language] Verbs have four moods (indicative, imperative, subjunctive, and optative) and three voices (active, middle, and passive), as well as three persons (first, second, and third) and various other forms.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greek-language] Verbs are conjugated through seven combinations of tenses and aspect (generally simply called "tenses"): the present, future, and imperfect are imperfective in aspect; the aorist, present perfect, pluperfect and future perfect are perfective in aspect.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greek-language] Most tenses display all four moods and three voices, although there is no future subjunctive or imperative.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greek-language] Also, there is no imperfect subjunctive, optative or imperative.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greek-language] The infinitives and participles correspond to the finite combinations of tense, aspect, and voice.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greek-language] The indicative of past tenses adds (conceptually, at least) a prefix /e-/, called the augment.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greek-language] This was probably originally a separate word, meaning something like "then", added because tenses in PIE had primarily aspectual meaning.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greek-language] The augment is added to the indicative of the aorist, imperfect, and pluperfect, but not to any of the other forms of the aorist (no other forms of the imperfect and pluperfect exist).
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greek-language] The two kinds of augment in Greek are syllabic and quantitative.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greek-language] The syllabic augment is added to stems beginning with consonants, and simply prefixes *e* (stems beginning with *r*, however, add *er*).
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greek-language] Some verbs augment irregularly; the most common variation is *e* → *ei*.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greek-language] The irregularity can be explained diachronically by the loss of *s* between vowels, or that of the letter *w*, which affected the augment when it was word-initial.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greek-language] In verbs with a preposition as a prefix, the augment is placed not at the start of the word, but between the preposition and the original verb.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greek-language] For example, προσ(-)βάλλω (I attack) goes to προσ**έ**βαλoν in the aorist.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greek-language] However compound verbs consisting of a prefix that is not a preposition retain the augment at the start of the word: αὐτο(-)μολῶ goes to **ηὐ**τομόλησα in the aorist.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greek-language] Following Homer's practice, the augment is sometimes not made in poetry, especially epic poetry.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greek-language] The augment sometimes substitutes for reduplication; see below.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greek-language] Almost all forms of the perfect, pluperfect, and future perfect reduplicate the initial syllable of the verb stem.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greek-language] Irregular duplication can be understood diachronically.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greek-language] For example, *lambanō* (root *lab*) has the perfect stem *eilēpha* (not **lelēpha*) because it was originally *slambanō*, with perfect *seslēpha*, becoming *eilēpha* through compensatory lengthening.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greek-language] Reduplication is also visible in the present tense stems of certain verbs.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greek-language] These stems add a syllable consisting of the root's initial consonant followed by *i*.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greek-language] A nasal stop appears after the reduplication in some verbs.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greek-language] The earliest extant examples of ancient Greek writing (c.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greek-language] 1450 BC) are in the syllabic script Linear B.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greek-language] Beginning in the 8th century BC, however, the Greek alphabet became standard, albeit with some variation among dialects.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greek-language] Early texts are written in boustrophedon style, but left-to-right became standard during the classic period.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greek-language] Modern editions of ancient Greek texts are usually written with accents and breathing marks, interword spacing, modern punctuation, and sometimes mixed case, but these were all introduced later.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greek-language] The beginning of Apology by Plato exemplifies Attic Greek from the Classical period of ancient Greek.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greek-language] How you, men of Athens, are feeling under the power of my accusers, I do not know: actually, even I myself almost forgot who I was because of them, they spoke so persuasively.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greek-language] And yet, loosely speaking, nothing they have said is true.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greek-language] The study of Ancient Greek in European countries in addition to Latin occupied an important place in the syllabus from the Renaissance until the beginning of the 20th century.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greek-language] This was true as well in the United States, where many of the nation's founders received a classically based education.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greek-language] Latin was emphasized in American colleges, but Greek also was required in the colonial and early national eras, and the study of ancient Greece became increasingly popular in the mid-to-late nineteenth century, the age of American philhellenism.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greek-language] In particular, female intellectuals of the era designated the mastering of ancient Greek as essential in becoming a "woman of letters".
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greek-language] Ancient Greek is still taught as a compulsory or optional subject especially at traditional or elite schools throughout Europe, such as public schools and grammar schools in the United Kingdom.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greek-language] In 2006/07, 15,000 pupils studied ancient Greek in Germany according to the Federal Statistical Office of Germany, and 280,000 pupils studied it in Italy.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greek-language] It is a compulsory subject alongside Latin in the humanities branch of the Spanish Baccalaureate.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greek-language] Ancient Greek is taught at most major universities worldwide, often combined with Latin as part of the study of classics.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greek-language] In 2010 it was offered in three primary schools in the UK, to boost children's language skills, and was one of seven foreign languages which primary schools could teach 2014 as part of a major drive to boost education standards.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greek-language] Ancient Greek is taught as a compulsory subject in all gymnasiums and lyceums in Greece.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greek-language] It appears to have ceased in 2010, having failed to gain the recognition and acceptance of teachers.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greek-language] Its first issue appeared in April 2015 as an annex to *Hebdomada Aenigmatum*.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greek-language] Alfred Rahlfs included a preface, a short history of the Septuagint text, and other front matter translated into ancient Greek in his 1935 edition of the Septuagint; Robert Hanhart also included the introductory remarks to the 2006 revised Rahlfs–Hanhart edition in the language as well.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greek-language] *Akropolis World News* reports weekly a summary of the most important news in ancient Greek.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greek-language] Ancient Greek is also used by organizations and individuals, mainly Greek, who wish to denote their respect, admiration or preference for the use of this language.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greek-language] This use is sometimes considered graphical, nationalistic or humorous.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greek-language] In any case, the fact that modern Greeks can still wholly or partly understand texts written in non-archaic forms of ancient Greek shows the affinity of the modern Greek language to its ancestral predecessor.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greek-language] Ancient Greek is often used in the coinage of modern technical terms in the European languages: see English words of Greek origin.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/ancient-greek-language] Latinized forms of ancient Greek roots are used in many of the scientific names of species and in scientific terminology.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/arrian] Arrian was born in Nicomedia (present-day İzmit), the provincial capital of Bithynia.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/arrian] Cassius Dio called him Flavius Arrianus Nicomediensis.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/arrian] Sources provide similar dates for his birth, within a few years prior to 90, 89, and 85–90 AD.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/arrian] The line of reasoning for dates belonging to 85–90 AD is because of Arrian being made a consul around 130 AD, and the usual age for this, during this period, being 42 years of age.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/arrian] His family was from the Greek provincial aristocracy, and his full name, *L.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/arrian] Flavius Arrianus*, indicates that he was a Roman citizen, suggesting that the citizenship went back several generations, probably to the time of the Roman conquest some 170 years before.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/arrian] Sometime during the second century AD (117 to 120 AD) while in Epirus, probably Nicopolis, Arrian attended lectures of Epictetus of Nicopolis, and proceeded within a time to fall into his pupillage, a fact attested to by Lucian.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/arrian] All that is known about the life of Epictetus is due to Arrian, in that Arrian left an *Encheiridion* (*Handbook*) of Epictetus' philosophy.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/arrian] After Epirus, he went to Athens, and while there, he became known as the "young Xenophon" as a consequence of the similarity of his relationship to Epictetus as Xenophon had to Socrates.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/arrian] For a period, some time about 126 AD, he was a friend of the emperor Hadrian's, who appointed him to the Senate.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/arrian] He was appointed to the position *consul suffectus* around 130 AD, and then, in 132 AD (although Howatson shows 131), he was made prefect or legate (governor) of Cappadocia by Hadrian, a service he continued for six years.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/arrian] Historian Cassius Dio states that not long after the Bar Kokhba revolt in Judea had been quelled, in 135 AD, King Pharasmanes II of Iberia caused the Alani to invade neighbouring territories, including Cappadocia, where their advance was robustly halted by Arrian's legions.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/arrian] Arrian referred to himself as "the second Xenophon", on account of his reputation and the esteem in which he was held.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/arrian] This quality is identified as *paideia* (παιδεία), which is the quality considered to be of one who is known as an educated and learned personage, i.e., one who is highly esteemed and important.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/arrian] The *Indica* and the *Anabasis* are the only works completely intact.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/arrian] His entire remaining *oeuvre* is known as *FGrH 156* to designate those collected fragments that exist.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/arrian] This work is the earliest extant work that is dated with any confidence.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/arrian] It is a writing addressed to Emperor Hadrian.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/arrian] Arrian was a pupil of Epictetus around 108 AD, and, according to his own account, he was moved to publish his notes of Epictetus' lectures, which are known as *Discourses of Epictetus*, by their unauthorized dissemination.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/arrian] According to George Long, Arrian noted from Epictetus' lectures for his private use and some time later made of these, the *Discourses*.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/arrian] Photius states that Arrian produced two books the *Dissertations* and the *Discourses*.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/arrian] The Discourses are also known as *Diatribai* and are apparently a verbatim recording of Epictetus' lectures.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/arrian] The *Enchiridion* is a short compendium of all Epictetus' philosophical principles.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/arrian] It is also known as a handbook, and A Mehl considers the *Enchiridion* to have been a *vade mecum* for Arrian.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/arrian] The *Enchiridion* is apparently a summary of the Discourses.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/arrian] JB Stockdale considered that Arrian wrote eight books of which four were lost by the Middle Ages and the remaining ones became the *Discourses*.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/arrian] In a comparison of the contents of the *Enchiridion* with the *Discourses*, it is apparent that the former contains material not present within the latter, suggesting an original lost source for the *Enchiridion*.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/arrian] The *Anabasis of Alexander* comprises seven books.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/arrian] Arrian used Xenophon's account of the March of Cyrus as the basis for this work.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/arrian] Three extant fragments are the *Vatican Palimpsest* (of the 10th century AD), PSI 12.1284 (Oxyrhynchus), and the *Gothenburg palimpsest* (of the 10th century also), these possibly stemming originally from Photius.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/arrian] The writing is about the successors of Alexander the Great, circa 323 – 321 or 319.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/arrian] A lost work of seventeen books, fragments of *Parthica* were maintained by the Suda and Stephanus of Byzantium.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/arrian] The work survives only in adaptations made later by Photius and Syncellus.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/arrian] Translated, the title is *History of the Parthians*.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/arrian] Arrian's aim in the work was to set forth events of the Parthian war of Trajan.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/arrian] The writing mentioned that the Parthians trace their origins to Artaxerxes II.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/arrian] A work of eight books, *Bibliotheca* (via Photius) states it is the fourth to have been written by Arrian.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/arrian] Written 136/137 AD (in the 20th year of Hadrian), *Techne Taktike* ('the art/craft of tactics') is a treatise on Roman cavalry and military tactics, and includes information on the nature, arms and discipline of the phalanx.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/arrian] The *hippika gymnasia* is a particular concern of Arrian in the treatise.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/arrian] Another translation of the title is *Ars tactica*, which, in Greek, is Τέχνη τακτική.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/arrian] This work has generally been considered in large part a panegyric to Hadrian, written for the occasion of his *vīcennālia*, although some scholars have argued that its second half may have had practical use.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/arrian] The work was inspired by and designed as an addition to an earlier exposition made by Xenophon, whom Arrian recognised to be the Ancient Greek authority on the subject of hunting with scent hounds.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/arrian] Within the work, Arrian explicitly identified the particular means of pursuing warfare as being based on Greek methods.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/arrian] There were also a number of monographs or biographies, including of Dion of Syracuse, Timoleon of Corinth, and Tilliborus, a brigand or robber of Asia Minor, which are now lost.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/arrian] Everything known of his life derives from the 9th century writing of Photius in his *Bibliotheca*, and from those few references which exist within Arrian's own writings.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/arrian] The knowledge of his consulship, is derived at the least from literature produced by Suidas.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/arrian] Arrian was also known of by Aulus Gellius.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/arrian] Pliny the Younger addressed seven of his epistles to him.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/arrian] Simplicius made a copy of the Enchiridion, which was transmitted under the name of the monastic father Nilus during the 5th century, and as a result found in every monastery library.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/arrian] Nicholas Blancard made translations of Arrian in 1663 and 1668.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/arrian] The voyage of Nearchus and *Periplus of the Erythrean Sea* were translated from the Greek by the then Dean of Westminster, William Vincent, and published in 1809.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/arrian] Vincent published a commentary in 1797 on *The voyage of Nearchus*.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/arrian] The work was also translated into French by M.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/arrian] Billecocq, under the auspices of the government (cf. p.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/athenaeus] Athenaeus himself states that he was the author of a treatise on the *thratta*, a type of fish mentioned by Archippus and other comic poets, and of a history of the Syrian kings.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/athenaeus] Of his works, only the fifteen-volume *Deipnosophistae* mostly survives.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/athenaeus] The *Deipnosophistae*, which means 'dinner-table philosophers', survives in fifteen books.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/athenaeus] The first two books, and parts of the third, eleventh and fifteenth, are extant only in epitome, but otherwise the work seems to be complete.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/athenaeus] It is an immense store-house of information, chiefly on matters connected with famous cooks, dining, but also containing remarks on music, songs, dances, philosophy, games, courtesans, and luxury.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/athenaeus] Nearly 800 writers and 2,500 separate works are referred to by Athenaeus; one of his characters (not necessarily to be identified with the historical author himself) boasts of having read 800 plays of Athenian Middle Comedy alone.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/athenaeus] Were it not for Athenaeus, much valuable information about the ancient world would be missing, and many ancient Greek authors such as Archestratus would be almost entirely unknown.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/athenaeus] Book XIII, for example, is an important source for the study of sexuality in classical and Hellenistic Greece, and a rare fragment of Theognetus' work survives in 3.63.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/athenaeus] The *Deipnosophistae* professes to be an account given by an individual named Athenaeus to his friend Timocrates of a banquet held at the house of Larensius (Λαρήνσιος; in Latin: Larensis), a wealthy book-collector and patron of the arts.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/athenaeus] It is thus a dialogue within a dialogue, after the manner of Plato, but the conversation extends to enormous length.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/athenaeus] The topics for discussion generally arise from the course of the dinner itself, but extend to literary and historical matters of every description, including abstruse points of grammar.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/athenaeus] The guests supposedly quote from memory.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/athenaeus] The actual sources of the material preserved in the *Deipnosophistae* remain obscure, but much of it probably comes at second hand from early scholars.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/athenaeus] The twenty-four named guests include individuals called Galen and Ulpian, but they are all probably fictitious personages, and the majority take no part in the conversation.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/athenaeus] If the character Ulpian is identical with the famous jurist, the *Deipnosophistae* may have been written after his death in 223; but the jurist was murdered by the Praetorian Guard, whereas Ulpian in Athenaeus dies a natural death.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/athenaeus] The complete version of the text, with the gaps noted above, is preserved in only one manuscript, conventionally referred to as A.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/athenaeus] The epitomized version of the text is preserved in two manuscripts, conventionally known as C and E.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/athenaeus] The standard edition of the text is Olson's Teubner.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/athenaeus] The standard numbering is drawn largely from Casaubon.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/athenaeus] The encyclopaedist and author Sir Thomas Browne wrote a short essay upon Athenaeus which reflects a revived interest in the *Banquet of the Learned* amongst scholars during the 17th century following its publication in 1612 by the Classical scholar Isaac Casaubon.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/dictionary-of-greek-and-roman-biography-and-mythology] The ***Dictionary of Greek and Roman Biography and Mythology*** is a biographical dictionary of classical antiquity, edited by William Smith and originally published in London by Taylor, Walton (and Maberly) and John Murray from 1844 to 1849 in three volumes of more than 3,700 pages.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/dictionary-of-greek-and-roman-biography-and-mythology] It is a classic work of 19th-century lexicography.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/dictionary-of-greek-and-roman-biography-and-mythology] The work is a companion to Smith's *Dictionary of Greek and Roman Antiquities* and *Dictionary of Greek and Roman Geography*.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/dictionary-of-greek-and-roman-biography-and-mythology] The work lists thirty-five authors in addition to the editor, who was also the author of the unsigned articles.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/dictionary-of-greek-and-roman-biography-and-mythology] The other authors were classical scholars, primarily from Oxford, Cambridge, Rugby School, and the University of Bonn, but some were from other institutions.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/dictionary-of-greek-and-roman-biography-and-mythology] Many of the mythological entries were the work of the German expatriate Leonhard Schmitz, who helped to popularise German classical scholarship in Britain.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/dictionary-of-greek-and-roman-biography-and-mythology] With respect to biographies, Smith intended to be comprehensive.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/dictionary-of-greek-and-roman-biography-and-mythology] Much of the value of the *Dictionary* consists not only in the depth and detail of the individual articles, but in the copious and specific citations to individual Greek and Roman writers, as well as modern scholarship from the Renaissance to the mid-nineteenth century.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/dictionary-of-greek-and-roman-biography-and-mythology] The articles frequently note variant traditions, disagreements among the authorities, and the interpretations of modern scholars.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/dictionary-of-greek-and-roman-biography-and-mythology] However, due to the variable numbering systems used in different editions of classical works, and the difficulty of recognizing typographical errors in citations, the original sources should still be checked.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/dictionary-of-greek-and-roman-biography-and-mythology] Many of the *Dictionary's* articles have been referred to in more recent works; Robert Graves has been accused of cribbing his impressive-looking source references from it when writing *The Greek Myths*.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/dictionary-of-greek-and-roman-biography-and-mythology] The work is now in the public domain, and is available in several places on the Internet.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/dictionary-of-greek-and-roman-biography-and-mythology] Smith's dictionary, however, does have substantial flaws.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/dictionary-of-greek-and-roman-biography-and-mythology] Troy and Knossos, for example, "the editors still regarded... as minstrels' fantasies".
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/dictionary-of-greek-and-roman-biography-and-mythology] Much is missing, especially more recent discoveries (such as Aristotle's *Constitution of the Athenians* or the decipherment of Linear B) and epigraphic material.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/dictionary-of-greek-and-roman-biography-and-mythology] More seriously, the context in which ancient evidence is viewed, analysed, reconciled, and understood has changed considerably in the intervening centuries.
[src:androsthenes-of-thasos/dictionary-of-greek-and-roman-biography-and-mythology] Modern theories and reconstructions of events are also not present, if only because they were published decades and centuries after Smith's *Dictionary*.
